.SS "4.1. How do I use the help files?"
.IX Subsection "4.1. How do I use the help files?"
Help can be found for all functions of Vim. In order to use it, use the
\&\*(L":help\*(R" command.  This will bring you to the main help page. On that first
page, you will find explanations on how to move around. Basically, you move
around in the help pages the same way you would in a read-only document.
You can jump to specific subjects by using tags. This can be done in two
ways:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&   * Use the "<Ctrl\-]>" command while standing on the name of a command
\&  or option. This only works when the tag is a keyword.
\&  "<Ctrl\-LeftMouse>" and "g<LeftMouse>" work just like "<Ctrl\-]>".
\&
\&   * use the ":tag <subject>" command. This works with all characters.
.Ve
.PP
Use \*(L"<Ctrl\-T>\*(R" to jump back to previous positions in the help files. Use
\&\*(L":q\*(R" to close the help window.
.PP
If you want to jump to a specific subject on the help pages, use \*(L":help
{subject}\*(R". If you don't know what to look for, try \*(L":help index\*(R" to get a
list of all available subjects. Use the standard search keys to locate the
information you want. You can abbreviate the \*(L":help\*(R" command as \*(L":h\*(R".
.PP
For searching the help, see the next Question 4.2.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help online-help\fR
.SS "4.2. How do I search for a keyword in the Vim help files?"
.IX Subsection "4.2. How do I search for a keyword in the Vim help files?"
a)  You can press the CTRL-D key after typing the help keyword to get a
 list of all the help keywords containing the supplied pattern. You can
 also use the meta characters like *, \e+, etc to specify the help
 search pattern:
.PP
\&\fB:help init<C\-D\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help str*()<C\-D\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help '*indent<C\-D\fR>
.PP
b)  You can press the Tab key after typing a partial help keyword to expand
 to the matching keyword. You can continue to press the Tab key to see
 other keyword matches.
.PP
c)  From the help window, you can use the \*(L":tag\*(R" command to search for
 keywords. For example,
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :tselect /window
\&
\& This command will list all the help keywords containing the text
\& "window". You can select one from the list and jump to it.
.Ve
.PP
d)  You can use the \*(L":helpgrep\*(R" command to search for the given text in
 all the help files. The quickfix window will be opened with all the
 matching lines.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help help-summary\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help c_CTRL\-D\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help c_<Tab\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help :tselect\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :help\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :helpgrep\fR
.SS "4.3. I am getting an error message E123, what did I do wrong?"
.IX Subsection "4.3. I am getting an error message E123, what did I do wrong?"
You can get more information about the error and the error message using:
.PP
\&\fB:help E123\fR
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help error-messages\fR
.SS "4.4. Where can I read about the various modes in Vim?"
.IX Subsection "4.4. Where can I read about the various modes in Vim?"
You can get information about the different modes in Vim by reading
.PP
\&\fB:help vim-modes\fR
.SS "4.5. How do I generate the Vim help tags file after adding a new Vim help file?"
.IX Subsection "4.5. How do I generate the Vim help tags file after adding a new Vim help file?"
You can use the \*(L":helptags\*(R" command to regenerate the Vim help tag file
from within Vim. For example:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :cd $VIMRUNTIME/doc
\& :helptags .
.Ve
.PP
To update all \*(L"doc\*(R" directories in your 'runtimepath', you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :helptags ALL
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :helptags\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help add-local-help\fR
.SS "4.6. Can I use compressed versions of the help files?"
.IX Subsection "4.6. Can I use compressed versions of the help files?"
Yes. You can compress the help files and still be able to view them with
Vim.  This makes accessing the help files a bit slower and requires the
\&\*(L"gzip\*(R" utility. Follow these steps to compress and use the Vim help files:
.PP
\&\- Compress all the help files using \*(L"gzip doc/*.txt\*(R".
.PP
\&\- Edit the \*(L"doc/tags\*(R" file and change the \*(L".txt\*(R" to \*(L".txt.gz\*(R" using
     :%s=\e(\et.*\e.txt\e)\et=\e1.gz\et=
.PP
\&\- Add the following line to your vimrc:
     set helpfile={dirname}/help.txt.gz
.PP
Where {dirname} is the directory where the help files are.  The gzip.vim
plugin supplied with the standard Vim distribution will take care of
decompressing the files.  You must make sure that \f(CW$VIMRUNTIME\fR is set to
where the other Vim files are, when they are not in the same location as
the compressed \*(L"doc\*(R" directory.
.PP
Note, that the :helpgrep command does not work with compressed help pages.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gzip-helpfile\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'helpfile'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gzip\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(CB$VIMRUNTIME\fB\fR
.SH "EDITING A FILE"
.IX Header "EDITING A FILE"
.SS "5.1. How do I load a file in Vim for editing?"
.IX Subsection "5.1. How do I load a file in Vim for editing?"
There are several ways to load a file for editing. The simplest is to
use the \*(L":e\*(R" (:edit) command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :e <filename>
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L":n\*(R" (:next) command to load files into Vim:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :n <filename(s)>
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L":args\*(R" command to load files into Vim:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :args <filename(s)>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help usr_07.txt\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help edit-files\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :edit\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :next_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :args_f\fR
.SS "5.2. How do I save the current file in another name (save as) and edit a new file?"
.IX Subsection "5.2. How do I save the current file in another name (save as) and edit a new file?"
You can use the \*(L":saveas\*(R" command to save the current file in another name:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :saveas <newfilename>
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively, you can also use the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :w <newfilename>
\& :edit #
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L":file\*(R" command, followed by \*(L":w\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :file <newfilename>
\& :w
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.7\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :saveas\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :file_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :w\fR
.SS "5.3. How do I change the current directory to the directory of the current file?"
.IX Subsection "5.3. How do I change the current directory to the directory of the current file?"
You can use the following command to change the current directory to the
directory of the current file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :cd %:p:h
.Ve
.PP
To automatically change the current directory to the directory of the
current file, simply set the option 'autochdir'.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set autochdir
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :cd\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :lcd\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help filename-modifiers\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help autocommand\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'acd'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIgetcwd()\fB\fR
.SS "5.4. How do I write a file without the line feed (\s-1EOL\s0) at the end of the file?"
.IX Subsection "5.4. How do I write a file without the line feed (EOL) at the end of the file?"
You can turn off the 'eol' option and turn on the 'binary' option to write
a file without the \s-1EOL\s0 at the end of the file:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :set binary
\& :set noeol
\& :w
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively, you can use:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set noeol
\& :w ++bin
.Ve
.PP
If you rather only like Vim not to write missing EOLs, you can reset the
\&'fixeol' option. This needs a Vim newer 7.4.785, so you should wrap this
in an if condition in your .vimrc like this:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& if exists(\*(Aq+fixeol\*(Aq)
\&     set nofixeol
\& endif
.Ve
.PP
This has the advantage of avoiding the many side effects that the
\&'binary' option has.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'endofline'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fixeol'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'binary'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 23.4\fR
.SS "5.5. How do I configure Vim to open a file at the last edited location?"
.IX Subsection "5.5. How do I configure Vim to open a file at the last edited location?"
Vim stores the cursor position of the last edited location for each buffer
in the '"' register. You can use the following autocmd in your .vimrc or
\&.gvimrc file to open a file at the last edited location:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& au BufReadPost * if line("\*(Aq\e"") > 0 && line("\*(Aq\e"") <= line("$") |
\&                      \e exe "normal! g\`\e"" | endif
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively, you can simply source the vimrc_example.vim file, which is
distributed with Vim.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help '"\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help last-position-jump\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help vimrc_example.vim\fR
.SS "5.6. When editing a file in Vim, which is being changed by an external application, Vim opens a warning window (like the confirm dialog) each time a change is detected. How do I disable this warning?"
.IX Subsection "5.6. When editing a file in Vim, which is being changed by an external application, Vim opens a warning window (like the confirm dialog) each time a change is detected. How do I disable this warning?"
You can set the Vim 'autoread' option to automatically read the file again
when it is changed outside of Vim:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set autoread
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the following autocommand:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& autocmd FileChangedShell *
\&       \e echohl WarningMsg |
\&       \e echo "File has been changed outside of vim." |
\&       \e echohl None
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'autoread'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help FileChangedShell\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help timestamp\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :checktime\fR
.SS "5.7. How do I edit a file whose name is under the cursor?"
.IX Subsection "5.7. How do I edit a file whose name is under the cursor?"
You can use the gf command to edit a file whose name is under the cursor.
You can use the CTRL-W f command to edit the file in a new window and
finally you can use CTRL-W gf top open a new tab page that contains the
file name under the cursor.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gf\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-W_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-W_gf\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'isfname'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'path'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'suffixesadd'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'includeexpr'\fR
.SS "5.8. How do I reload/re\-edit the current file?"
.IX Subsection "5.8. How do I reload/re-edit the current file?"
You can use the \*(L":edit\*(R" command, without specifying a file name, to reload
the current file.  If you have made modifications to the file, you can use
\&\*(L":edit!\*(R" to force the reload of the current file (you will lose your
modifications, but depending on your 'undoreload' settings, those
changes might be saved into the undo history).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :edit\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :edit!\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'confirm'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'undoreload'\fR
.SS "5.9. How do I autosave a file periodically?"
.IX Subsection "5.9. How do I autosave a file periodically?"
Vim doesn't support auto-saving a file periodically.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'updatetime'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CursorHold\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help swap-file\fR
.SS "5.10. How do I open a file in read-only mode?"
.IX Subsection "5.10. How do I open a file in read-only mode?"
You can open a file in read-only mode using the \*(L":view\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :view <filename>
.Ve
.PP
This command sets the 'readonly' option for the opened buffer. You can also
use the \*(L"\-R\*(R" command-line option to open a file in read-only mode:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-R <filename>
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the symbolic link executable \*(L"view\*(R" to open a file in
read-only mode from the command-line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ view <filename>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.6\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'readonly'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'modifiable'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :view\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :sview\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help view\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-M\fR
.SS "5.11. How do I open a file for editing without saving the modifications to the current file?"
.IX Subsection "5.11. How do I open a file for editing without saving the modifications to the current file?"
You can open a file for editing without saving the modifications to the
current file and without losing the changes using one of the following
methods:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :split <new_filename>
\& :new <new_filename>
.Ve
.PP
You can also set the 'hidden' option and edit a new file:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set hidden
\& :e <new_filename>
.Ve
.PP
If you want to discard the changes made to the current file and load
another file for editing, then you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :e! <new_filename>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :edit!_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'hidden'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :split\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :new\fR
.SS "5.12. How do I reduce the loading time for very large files in Vim?"
.IX Subsection "5.12. How do I reduce the loading time for very large files in Vim?"
You can use the following settings to reduce the loading time for
very large files in Vim:
.PP
.Vb 6
\& :set lazyredraw
\& :set noswapfile
\& :set undolevels=\-1
\& :set eventignore=all
\& :set nohidden
\& :set syntax=off
.Ve
.PP
Note that the above settings will disable many Vim features including the
following: Swap files support for crash recovery, undo support, syntax
highlighting, filetype detection and other autocommand based features.
.PP
There is also the LargeFile plugin available at
http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=1506
which automatically sets these options, when working with large files
(it is configurable, what is considered to be a large file, by default,
it is 100MB).
.SH "EDITING MULTIPLE FILES"
.IX Header "EDITING MULTIPLE FILES"
.SS "6.1. How do I open multiple files at once from within Vim?"
.IX Subsection "6.1. How do I open multiple files at once from within Vim?"
Make a difference between args, buffers, tabs and windows. They are all
different things in \s-1VIM.\s0
.PP
args is a list of arguments. Buffers are place to edit text, almost
always attached to a file but not necessarily. Window is a place for a
buffer and tab is set of windows, better name would be 'layout'.
.PP
There are several ways to open multiple files at once from within Vim. You
can use the \*(L":next\*(R" command to specify a group of files:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :next f1.txt f2.txt
\& :next *.c
.Ve
.PP
You can use the :args command to specify a group of files as arguments:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :args f1.txt f2.txt
\& :args *.c
.Ve
.PP
After loading the files, you can use the \*(L":next\*(R" and \*(L":prev\*(R" command to
switch between the files.
.PP
To execute command for all files in argument-list use \*(L":argdo\*(R"
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.2\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :next\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :args_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help argument-list\fR
.SS "6.2. How do I switch between multiple files/buffers in Vim?"
.IX Subsection "6.2. How do I switch between multiple files/buffers in Vim?"
To list all buffers use \*(L":ls\*(R", to list buffers without file attached to
(also known as unlisted buffers, ex. scratch buffer and help-window) use
\&\*(L":ls!\*(R"
.PP
There are several ways to switch between multiple files. You can use the
\&\*(L":buffer\*(R" command to switch between multiple files. You can also shorten
command as \*(L":b\*(R" and use only part of the filename. For example,
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :buffer file1
\& :buffer file2
\& :b e2
.Ve
.PP
You can also use <\s-1TAB\s0> after \*(L":b\*(R" for autocompletion. Try also \*(L":b\*(R"
followed by <CTRL\-d> to see all available buffers. This works also for
\&\*(L":e\*(R".
.PP
You can also use the CTRL\-^ key to switch between buffers. By specifying a
count before pressing the key, you can edit the buffer with that number.
Without the count, you can edit the alternate buffer by pressing CTRL\-^
.PP
You can also use the \*(L":e #\*(R" command to edit a particular buffer:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :e #5
.Ve
.PP
To close a buffer use \*(L":bd\*(R" \-command.
.PP
To execute command for all files in buffer-list use \*(L":bufdo\*(R"
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help edit-files\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :buffer\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-^\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help alternate-file\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 22.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.3\fR
.SS "6.3. How do I open several files in Vim, with each file in a separate window/tab?"
.IX Subsection "6.3. How do I open several files in Vim, with each file in a separate window/tab?"
You can use the \-o and \-O Vim command line arguments to open multiple files
in separate horizontally or vertically split Vim windows. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-o3 f1.txt f2.txt f3.txt
.Ve
.PP
The above command will open the files f1.txt, f2.txt and f3.txt in three
separate horizontally split Vim windows.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-O3 f1.txt f2.txt f3.txt
.Ve
.PP
The above command will open the files f1.txt, f2.txt and f3.txt in three
separate vertically split Vim windows.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-p f1.txt f2.txt f3.txt
.Ve
.PP
The above command will open the files f1.txt, f2.txt and f3.txt in three
separate tab windows. The option 'tabpagemax' defines, how many tabpages
can be opened at the same time, by default it is set to 10.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \-o\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-p\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help startup-options\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'tabpagemax'\fR
.ie n .SS "6.4. How do I configure Vim to autoload several files at once similar to ""work-sets"" or ""projects""?"
.el .SS "6.4. How do I configure Vim to autoload several files at once similar to ``work-sets'' or ``projects''?"
.IX Subsection "6.4. How do I configure Vim to autoload several files at once similar to work-sets or projects?"
You can use the \*(L":mksession\*(R" and the \*(L":mkview\*(R" commands to autoload several
files in Vim.
.PP
The \*(L":mksession\*(R" command creates a Vim script that restores the current
editing session. You can use the \*(L":source\*(R" command to source the file
produced by the mksession command.
.PP
The \*(L":mkview\*(R" command creates a Vim script that restores the contents of
the current window. You can use the \*(L":loadview\*(R" command to load the view
for the current file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 21.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 21.5\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help views-sessions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'sessionoptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mksession\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :source\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help v:this_session\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mkview\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :loadview\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viewdir'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help buffers\fR
.SS "6.5. Is it possible to open multiple top level windows in a single instance of Vim similar to Nedit or Emacs?"
.IX Subsection "6.5. Is it possible to open multiple top level windows in a single instance of Vim similar to Nedit or Emacs?"
No. It is currently not possible to open multiple top-level windows in a
single instance of Vim. This feature is in the todo list.
.SS "6.6. How do I browse/explore directories from within Vim?"
.IX Subsection "6.6. How do I browse/explore directories from within Vim?"
You can use the netrw.vim plugin, supplied with the standard Vim
installation, to browse/explore directories from within Vim. You can start
the file explorer using one of the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& :e <directory>
\& :Explore
\& :Sexplore
\& :Vexplore
\& :Texplore
.Ve
.PP
From the file explorer, you can browse through directories, rename, delete
and edit files.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help netrw.vim\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 22.1\fR
.SS "6.7. How do I edit files over a network using ftp/scp/rcp/http?"
.IX Subsection "6.7. How do I edit files over a network using ftp/scp/rcp/http?"
You can use the netrw.vim plugin, supplied with the standard Vim package,
to edit files over a network using ftp/scp/rcp/http. Using this plugin, Vim
will transparently load and save the files over ftp/scp/rcp/http. For
example, to edit a file over ftp, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim ftp://machine/path
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read:
.PP
\&\fB:help netrw.vim\fR
.SH "BACKUP"
.IX Header "BACKUP"
.ie n .SS "7.1. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a ""~"" character at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file? (or) How do I disable the Vim backup file feature?"
.el .SS "7.1. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a ``~'' character at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file? (or) How do I disable the Vim backup file feature?"
.IX Subsection "7.1. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a ~ character at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file? (or) How do I disable the Vim backup file feature?"
You have set the 'backup' option, so Vim creates a backup file when saving
the original file. You can stop Vim from creating the backup file, by
clearing the option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nobackup
.Ve
.PP
Note that, by default this option is turned off. You have explicitly
enabled the 'backup' option in one of the initialization files. You may
also have to turn off the 'writebackup' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nowritebackup
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help backup-table\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backup'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'writebackup'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupskip'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupdir'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupext'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupcopy'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help backup\fR
.ie n .SS "7.2. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a ""un~"" extension at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file (or) How do I disable the Vim undofile feature?"
.el .SS "7.2. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a ``un~'' extension at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file (or) How do I disable the Vim undofile feature?"
.IX Subsection "7.2. When I edit and save files, Vim creates a file with the same name as the original file and a un~ extension at the end. How do I stop Vim from creating this file (or) How do I disable the Vim undofile feature?"
Vim 7.3 contains as new feature persistent undo, that is, undo information
won't be lost when quitting Vim and be stored in a file that ends with .un~
You have set the 'undofile' option, so Vim creates an undo file when saving
the original file. You can stop Vim from creating the backup file, by
clearing the option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set noundofile
.Ve
.PP
Note that, by default this option is turned off. You have explicitly
enabled the 'undofile' option in one of the initialization files. If you
want your undofiles to be stored only in a particular directory, you can
point the 'undodir' option to a directory that will contain all your
aggregated undofiles.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'undodir'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'undofile'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help undo-persistence\fR
.SS "7.3. How do I configure Vim to store all the backup files in a particular directory?"
.IX Subsection "7.3. How do I configure Vim to store all the backup files in a particular directory?"
You can configure Vim to store all the backup files in a particular
directory using the 'backupdir' option. For example, to store all the
backup files in the ~/backup directory, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set backupdir=~/backup
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 07.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupdir'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help backup\fR
.SS "7.4. When I save a file with Vim, the file permissions are changed. How do I configure Vim to save a file without changing the file permissions?"
.IX Subsection "7.4. When I save a file with Vim, the file permissions are changed. How do I configure Vim to save a file without changing the file permissions?"
This may happen, if the 'backupcopy' option is set to 'no' or 'auto'. Note
that the default value for this option is set in such a way that this will
correctly work in most of the cases. If the default doesn't work for you,
try setting the 'backupcopy' option to 'yes' to keep the file permission
when saving a file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set backupcopy=yes
.Ve
.PP
This applies, only if you have configured Vim to make a backup whenever
overwriting a file. By default, Vim will not backup files.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backupcopy'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help backup\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backup'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'writebackup'\fR
.SH "BUFFERS"
.IX Header "BUFFERS"
.SS "8.1. I have made some modifications to a buffer. How do I edit another buffer without saving the modified buffer and also without losing the modifications?"
.IX Subsection "8.1. I have made some modifications to a buffer. How do I edit another buffer without saving the modified buffer and also without losing the modifications?"
You can set the 'hidden' option to edit a file without losing modifications
to the current file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set hidden
.Ve
.PP
By setting the 'hidden' option, you can also save the modification history
(undo-history) for the buffer. Otherwise, as you switch between files, the
undo-history will be lost (unless you use persistent undofiles).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'hidden'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hidden-quit\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :hide\fR
.SS "8.2. How do I configure Vim to auto-save a modified buffer when switching to another buffer?"
.IX Subsection "8.2. How do I configure Vim to auto-save a modified buffer when switching to another buffer?"
You can set the 'autowrite' option to auto-save a modified buffer when
switching to another buffer:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set autowrite
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'autowrite'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'autowriteall'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'hidden'\fR
.SS "8.3. How do I replace the buffer in the current window with a blank buffer?"
.IX Subsection "8.3. How do I replace the buffer in the current window with a blank buffer?"
You can use the \*(L":enew\*(R" command to load an empty buffer in place of the
buffer in the current window.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :enew\fR
.SS "8.4. Is there a keyboard shortcut to load a buffer by the buffer number?"
.IX Subsection "8.4. Is there a keyboard shortcut to load a buffer by the buffer number?"
You can use the CTRL\-^ command to load a buffer by specifying the buffer
number. For example, to load buffer number 5, you have to use the 5 CTRL\-^
command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-^\fR
.SS "8.5. How do I open all the current buffers in separate windows?"
.IX Subsection "8.5. How do I open all the current buffers in separate windows?"
You can use the \*(L":ball\*(R" or \*(L":sball\*(R" commands to open all the buffers
in the buffer list:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :ball
.Ve
.PP
If you want all buffers to be opened in new tabs, simply prefix the :tab
command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :tab :sball
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :ball\fR
.SS "8.6. How do I close (delete) a buffer without exiting Vim?"
.IX Subsection "8.6. How do I close (delete) a buffer without exiting Vim?"
You can use any of \*(L":bdelete\*(R", \*(L":bwipeout\*(R" or \*(L":bunload\*(R" commands to
delete a buffer without exiting Vim. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :bdelete file1
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :bdelete\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :bwipeout\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :bunload\fR
.ie n .SS "8.7. When I use the command "":%bd"" to delete all the buffers, not all the buffers are deleted. Why?"
.el .SS "8.7. When I use the command ``:%bd'' to delete all the buffers, not all the buffers are deleted. Why?"
.IX Subsection "8.7. When I use the command :%bd to delete all the buffers, not all the buffers are deleted. Why?"
In the \*(L":%bd\*(R" command, the '%' range will be replaced with the starting and
ending line numbers in the current buffer. Instead of using '%' as the
range, you should specify numbers for the range. For example, to delete all
the buffers, you can use the command \*(L":1,9999bd\*(R".
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :bd\fR
.PP
(This behaviour has been fixed with patch 7.4.530)
.SS "8.8. How do I display the buffer number of the current buffer/file?"
.IX Subsection "8.8. How do I display the buffer number of the current buffer/file?"
You can use 2<\s-1CTRL\-G\s0> command to display the buffer number for the current
file/buffer. Note the use of count before the CTRL-G command. If the count
is greater than 1, then Vim will display the buffer number.
.PP
You can also use the following command to display the current buffer
number:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :echo bufnr("%")
.Ve
.PP
You can also include the \*(L"%n\*(R" field to the 'statusline' option to display
the current buffer number on the statusline.
.PP
For more information read,
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-G\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIbufnr()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :echo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'statusline'\fR
.SS "8.9. How do I delete a buffer without closing the window in which the buffer is displayed?"
.IX Subsection "8.9. How do I delete a buffer without closing the window in which the buffer is displayed?"
You can use the following command to open the next buffer and delete
the current buffer.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :bnext | bdelete #
.Ve
.PP
For more information read,
.PP
\&\fB:help :bnext\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :bdelete\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :buffers\fR
.SS "8.10. How do I map the tab key to cycle through and open all the buffers?"
.IX Subsection "8.10. How do I map the tab key to cycle through and open all the buffers?"
You can use the following two map commands, to map the CTRL-Tab key to open
the next buffer and the CTRL-SHIFT-Tab key to open the previous buffer:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :nnoremap <C\-Tab> :bnext<CR>
\& :nnoremap <S\-C\-Tab> :bprevious<CR>
.Ve
.PP
Note, this might not work in the terminal version of Vim.
.PP
For more information read,
.PP
\&\fB:help :bnext\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :bprevious\fR
.SH "WINDOWS"
.IX Header "WINDOWS"
.SS "9.1. What is the difference between a Vim window and a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "9.1. What is the difference between a Vim window and a buffer?"
A Vim buffer is a file loaded into memory for editing. The original file
remains unchanged until you write the buffer to the file. A Vim window is a
viewport onto a buffer. You can use multiple windows on one buffer or
several windows on different buffers.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help usr_08.txt\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 22.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help windows-intro\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Q_wi\fR
.SS "9.2. How do I increase the width of a Vim window?"
.IX Subsection "9.2. How do I increase the width of a Vim window?"
You can increase the width of a Vim window using one of the following
commands:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :vert resize +N
\& :vert resize \-N
\& :vert resize N
.Ve
.PP
You can also use CTRL-W < or CTRL-W > or CTRL-W | commands.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :vertical\-resize\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \s-1CTRL\-W_\s0\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-W_<\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help window-resize\fR
.SS "9.3. How do I zoom into or out of a window?"
.IX Subsection "9.3. How do I zoom into or out of a window?"
You can zoom into a window (close all the windows except the current
window) using the \*(L"CTRL-W o\*(R" command or the \*(L":only\*(R" ex command.
.PP
You can use the \*(L"CTRL-W _\*(R" command or the \*(L":resize\*(R" ex command to increase
the current window height to the highest possible without closing other
windows.
.PP
You can use the \*(L"CTRL-W |\*(R" command or the \*(L":vertical resize\*(R" ex command to
increase the current window width to the highest possible without closing
other windows.
.PP
You can use the \*(L"CTRL-W =\*(R" command to make the height and width of all the
windows equal.
.PP
You can also set the following options to get better results with the above
commands:
.PP
Method 1:
Set the 'winminheight' option to 0:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set winminheight=0
.Ve
.PP
By default, this option is set to 1.
This option controls the minimum height of an inactive window (when it is
not the current window).  When the 'winminheight' option is set to 0, only
the status line will be displayed for inactive windows.
.PP
Method 2:
Set the 'noequalalways' option and set the 'winheight' option to a large
value (like 99999):
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set noequalalways
\& :set winheight=99999
.Ve
.PP
Now, the active window will always open to its maximum size, while the
other windows will stay present, but shrunken to just a status line.
.PP
With any of the above mentioned methods, you cannot restore the window
layout after zooming into a window.  If you want to restore the Vim window
layout after zooming into a window, you can use the ZoomWin plugin. You can
download this plugin from the Vim online website at:
.PP
http://vim.sourceforge.net/scripts/script.php?script_id=508
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-W_o\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help window-resize\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'winminheight'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'equalalways'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'winheight'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 08.3\fR
.SS "9.4. How do I execute an ex command on all the open buffers or open windows or all the files in the argument list?"
.IX Subsection "9.4. How do I execute an ex command on all the open buffers or open windows or all the files in the argument list?"
You can use the \*(L":bufdo\*(R" command to execute an ex command on all the open
buffers.  You can use the \*(L":windo\*(R" command to execute an ex command on all
the open windows.  You can use the \*(L":argdo\*(R" command to execute an ex
command on all the files specified in the argument list. And finally you
can use the \*(L":tabdo\*(R" command to execute an ex command in all open tab pages.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :windo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :bufdo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :argdo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :tabdo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 26.3\fR
.SH "MOTION"
.IX Header "MOTION"
.SS "10.1. How do I jump to the beginning (first line) or end (last line) of a file?"
.IX Subsection "10.1. How do I jump to the beginning (first line) or end (last line) of a file?"
You can use 'G' command to jump to the last line in the file and the 'gg'
command to jump to the first line in the file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help G\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gg\fR
.SS "10.2. In insert mode, when I press the <Esc> key to go to command mode, the cursor moves one character to the left (except when the cursor is on the first character of the line). Is it possible to change this behavior to keep the cursor at the same column?"
.IX Subsection "10.2. In insert mode, when I press the <Esc> key to go to command mode, the cursor moves one character to the left (except when the cursor is on the first character of the line). Is it possible to change this behavior to keep the cursor at the same column?"
No. It is not possible to change this behavior. The cursor is *always*
positioned on a valid character (unless you have virtual-edit mode
enabled). So, if you are appending text to the end of a line, when you
return to command mode the cursor *must* drop back onto the last character
you typed. For consistency sake, the cursor drops back everywhere, even if
you are in the middle of a line.
.PP
You can use the CTRL-O or CTRL\-\e CTRL-O command in insert mode to execute a
single ex command and return back to insert mode without moving the cursor
column.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'virtualedit'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-\e_CTRL\-O\fR
.SS "10.3. How do I configure Vim to maintain the horizontal cursor position when scrolling with the <Page Up>, <Page Down>, etc keys?"
.IX Subsection "10.3. How do I configure Vim to maintain the horizontal cursor position when scrolling with the <Page Up>, <Page Down>, etc keys?"
You can reset the 'startofline' option to keep the cursor at the same
horizontal location when scrolling text:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nostartofline
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'startofline'\fR
.SS "10.4. Some lines in a file are more than the screen width and they are all wrapped. When I use the j, k keys to move from one line to the next, the cursor is moved to the next line in the file instead of the next line on the screen. How do I move from one screen line to the next?"
.IX Subsection "10.4. Some lines in a file are more than the screen width and they are all wrapped. When I use the j, k keys to move from one line to the next, the cursor is moved to the next line in the file instead of the next line on the screen. How do I move from one screen line to the next?"
You can use the gj and gk commands to move from one screen line to the
next/previous screen line. The j and k commands move the cursor from one
file line to the next file line. You can also avoid the line wrapping by
resetting the 'wrap' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nowrap
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gj\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gk\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'wrap'\fR
.PP
You can use the following mappings:
.PP
.Vb 6
\& :map <Up> gk
\& :imap <Up> <C\-o>gk
\& :map <Down> gj
\& :imap <Down> <C\-o>gj
\& :noremap j gj
\& :noremap k gk
.Ve
.SS "10.5. What is the definition of a sentence, paragraph and section in Vim?"
.IX Subsection "10.5. What is the definition of a sentence, paragraph and section in Vim?"
A sentence is defined as ending at a '.', '!' or '?' followed by either the
end of a line, or by a space (or two) or tab. Which characters and the
number of spaces needed to constitute a sentence ending is determined by
the 'joinspaces' and 'cpoptions' options.
.PP
A paragraph begins after each empty line, and also at each of a set of
paragraph macros, specified by the pairs of characters in the 'paragraphs'
option.
.PP
A section begins after a form-feed (<C\-L>) in the first column and at each
of a set of section macros, specified by the pairs of characters in the
\&'sections' option.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help sentence\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'joinspaces'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cpoptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help paragraph\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help section\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help word\fR
.SS "10.6. How do I jump to beginning or end of a sentence, paragraph or a section?"
.IX Subsection "10.6. How do I jump to beginning or end of a sentence, paragraph or a section?"
You can use the following motion commands to jump to the beginning or end
of a sentence or a paragraph or a section:
.PP
.Vb 9
\&   motion  position    where
\&   (       beginning   current sentence
\&   )       end         current sentence
\&   {       beginning   current paragraph
\&   }       end         current paragraph
\&   []      end         previous section
\&   [[      beginning   current section
\&   ][      end         current section
\&   ]]      beginning   next section
.Ve
.PP
Each of these motions can be preceded by a number which will extend the
jump forward (or backward).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help object-motions\fR
.SS "10.7. I have lines in a file that extends beyond the right extent of the screen. How do I move the Vim view to the right to see the text off the screen?"
.IX Subsection "10.7. I have lines in a file that extends beyond the right extent of the screen. How do I move the Vim view to the right to see the text off the screen?"
You can use one of the following commands to horizontally scroll the screen
to the left or right:
.PP
.Vb 6
\& zl \- scroll to the left
\& zh \- scroll to the right
\& zL \- scroll half a screenwidth to the left
\& zH \- scroll half a screenwidth to the right
\& zs \- scroll to position the cursor at the start of the screen
\& ze \- scroll to position the cursor at the end of the screen
.Ve
.PP
You can use the g0 command to move the cursor to the first character of the
screen line and the g$ command to move the cursor to the last character of
the screen line without scrolling the screen.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help scroll-horizontal\fR
.SS "10.8. How do I scroll two or more buffers simultaneously?"
.IX Subsection "10.8. How do I scroll two or more buffers simultaneously?"
You can set the \*(L"scrollbind\*(R" option for each of the buffers to scroll them
simultaneously.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'scrollbind'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help scroll-binding\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'scrollopt'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cursorbind'\fR
.SS "10.9. When I use my arrow keys, Vim changes modes, inserts weird characters in my document but doesn't move the cursor properly. What's going on?"
.IX Subsection "10.9. When I use my arrow keys, Vim changes modes, inserts weird characters in my document but doesn't move the cursor properly. What's going on?"
There are a couple of things that could be going on: either you are using
Vim over a slow connection or Vim doesn't understand the key sequence that
your keyboard is generating.
.PP
If you are working over a slow connection (such as a 2400 bps modem), you
can try to set the 'timeout' or 'ttimeout' option. These options, combined
with the 'timeoutlen' and 'ttimeoutlen' options, may fix the problem.
.PP
The preceding procedure will not work correctly if your terminal sends key
codes that Vim does not understand. In this situation, your best option is
to map your key sequence to a matching cursor movement command and save
these mappings in a file. You can then \*(L":source\*(R" the file whenever you work
from that terminal.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'timeout'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ttimeout'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'timeoutlen'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ttimeoutlen'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :map\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help vt100\-cursor\-keys\fR
.SS "10.10. How do I configure Vim to move the cursor to the end of the previous line, when the left arrow key is pressed and the cursor is currently at the beginning of a line?"
.IX Subsection "10.10. How do I configure Vim to move the cursor to the end of the previous line, when the left arrow key is pressed and the cursor is currently at the beginning of a line?"
You can add the '<' flag to the 'whichwrap' option to configure Vim to move
the cursor to the end of the previous line, when the left arrow key is
pressed and the cursor is currently at the beginning of a line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set whichwrap+=<
.Ve
.PP
Similarly, to move the cursor the beginning of the next line, when the
right arrow key is  pressed and the cursor is currently at the end of a
line, add the '>' flag to the 'whichwrap' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set whichwrap+=>
.Ve
.PP
The above will work only in normal and visual modes. To use this in insert
and replace modes, add the '[' and ']' flags respectively.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'whichwrap'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 05.7\fR
.SS "10.11. How do I configure Vim to stay only in insert mode (modeless editing)?"
.IX Subsection "10.11. How do I configure Vim to stay only in insert mode (modeless editing)?"
You can set the 'insertmode' option to configure Vim to stay only in insert
mode:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set insertmode
.Ve
.PP
By setting this option, you can use Vim as a modeless editor. If you press
the <Esc> key, Vim will not go to the normal mode. To execute a single
normal mode command, you can press CTRL-O followed by the normal mode
command.  To execute more than one normal command, you can use CTRL-L
followed by the commands. To return to insert mode, press the <Esc> key. To
disable this option, reset the 'insertmode' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set noinsertmode
.Ve
.PP
You can also start vim using the \*(L"evim\*(R" command or you can use \*(L"vim \-y\*(R" to
use Vim as a modeless editor.
.PP
You can also start Vim in insert mode using the \*(L":startinsert\*(R" ex command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'insertmode'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :startinsert\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :stopinsert\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-L\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help evim\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help evim-keys\fR
.SS "10.12. How do I display some context lines when scrolling text?"
.IX Subsection "10.12. How do I display some context lines when scrolling text?"
You can set the 'scrolloff' option to display a minimal number of screen
lines (context) above and below the cursor.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set scrolloff=10
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'scrolloff'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'sidescrolloff'\fR
.SS "10.13. How do I go back to previous cursor locations?"
.IX Subsection "10.13. How do I go back to previous cursor locations?"
You can go back to the cursor location before the latest jump using the ''
or `` command. You can use the CTRL-O command to go back to older cursor
positions and the CTRL-I command to go to the newer cursor positions in the
jump list.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 03.10\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help mark-motions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help jump-motions\fR
.SH "SEARCHING TEXT"
.IX Header "SEARCHING TEXT"
.SS "11.1. After I searched for a text with a pattern, all the matched text stays highlighted. How do I turn off the highlighting temporarily/permanently?"
.IX Subsection "11.1. After I searched for a text with a pattern, all the matched text stays highlighted. How do I turn off the highlighting temporarily/permanently?"
The 'hlsearch' option controls whether all the matches for the last
searched pattern are highlighted or not. By default, this option is not
enabled. If this option is set in a system-wide vimrc file, then you can
turn off the search highlighting by using the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nohlsearch
.Ve
.PP
To temporarily turn off the search highlighting, use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :nohlsearch
.Ve
.PP
You can also clear the search highlighting, by searching for a pattern that
is not in the current file (for example, search for the pattern 'asdf').
.PP
You can use this mapping, to clear the search highlighting when
redrawing the window pressing <\s-1CTRL\-L\s0>
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :nnoremap <silent> <C\-L> <C\-L>:nohls<CR>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'hlsearch'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :nohlsearch\fR
.SS "11.2. How do I enter a carriage return character in a search pattern?"
.IX Subsection "11.2. How do I enter a carriage return character in a search pattern?"
You can either use '\er' or <\s-1CTRL\-V\s0><\s-1CTRL\-M\s0> to enter a carriage return
character in a pattern. In Vim scripts, it is better to use '\er' for the
carriage return character.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help sub-replace-special\fR
.SS "11.3. How do I search for the character ^M?"
.IX Subsection "11.3. How do I search for the character ^M?"
You can enter the ^M character in a search command by first pressing the
CTRL-V key and then pressing the CTRL-M key.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /^V^M
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L"\er\*(R" character. In Vim scripts, \*(L"\er\*(R" is preferred.
.PP
For more information, read
