.SS "11.18. How do I search for a character by its \s-1ASCII\s0 value?"
.IX Subsection "11.18. How do I search for a character by its ASCII value?"
You can search for a character by its \s-1ASCII\s0 value by pressing CTRL-V
followed by the decimal or hexadecimal or octal value of that character in
the search \*(L"/\*(R" command.  To determine the \s-1ASCII\s0 value of a character you
can use the \*(L":ascii\*(R" or the \*(L"ga\*(R" command.
.PP
For example, to search for the \s-1ASCII\s0 character with value 188 (??), you can
use one of the following search commands:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& /<CTRL\-V>188
\& /<CTRL\-V>o274
\& /<CTRL\-V>xBC
\& /<CTRL\-V>u00bc
.Ve
.PP
You can also search for the character with the decimal/octal/hex number
using a collation [] like this:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& /[\ed188]
\& /[\eo274]
\& /[\exbc]
\& /[\eu00bc]
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively, you can use the special atom \e%d \e%o \e%x \e%u:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& /\e%d188
\& /\e%o274
\& /\e%xbc
\& /\e%u00bc
.Ve
.PP
Or you use digraphs to enter the character. For example enter:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /CTRL\-K14
.Ve
.PP
to search for the above character.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-V_digit\fR
.PP
