.SS "11.19. How do I search for long lines?"
.IX Subsection "11.19. How do I search for long lines?"
You can search for long lines or lines containing more than a specific
number of characters using the Vim regular-expressions in the search
command. For example, to search for all the lines containing more than 80
characters, you can use one of the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& /^.\e{80}.\e+$
\& /^.*\e%>80c.*$
\& /^.*\e%>80v.*$
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e{\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e%c\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e%v\fR
.SS "11.20. How do I display all the lines in the current buffer that contain a specified pattern?"
.IX Subsection "11.20. How do I display all the lines in the current buffer that contain a specified pattern?"
You can use the following command to display all the lines in the current
buffer that contain a specified pattern:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/<pattern>/p
.Ve
.PP
For example, the following command will display all the lines in the
current buffer that contain \*(L"vim\*(R":
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/vim/p
.Ve
.PP
Since :p is the default command to be executed for the ex command :g, you
can also use:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/vim
.Ve
.PP
If you also want the corresponding line numbers, then you can use the
following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/<pattern>/#
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :global\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :print\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :number\fR
.SS "11.21. How do I search for a text string that spans multiple lines?"
.IX Subsection "11.21. How do I search for a text string that spans multiple lines?"
You can search for a text string that spans multiple lines using the \e_x
regular expression atom. For example, to search for the text string \*(L"Hello
World\*(R", you can use the following search command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /Hello\e_sWorld
.Ve
.PP
This will match the word \*(L"Hello\*(R" followed by a newline character and then
the word \*(L"World\*(R" at the beginning of the next line. This will also match
the word \*(L"Hello\*(R" immediately followed by a space character and then the
word \*(L"World\*(R". When searching for the \*(L"Hello World\*(R" string, to include the
space characters at the end and beginning of the line, you can use the
following search command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /Hello\e_s\e+World
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 27.8\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help pattern-atoms\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e_\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help pattern-searches\fR
.SS "11.22. How do I search for a pattern within the specified range of lines in a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "11.22. How do I search for a pattern within the specified range of lines in a buffer?"
You can search for a pattern within a range of lines using the \e%>l
and \e%<l regular expression atoms.
.PP
For example, to search for the word 'white' between the lines 10 and 30 in
a buffer, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /white\e%>9l\e%<31l
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e%l\fR
.SS "11.23. How do I clear the last searched pattern?"
.IX Subsection "11.23. How do I clear the last searched pattern?"
The last searched pattern is stored in the \*(L"/\*(R" register. You can clear
this register using the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let @/=""
.Ve
.PP
To clear the last search pattern whenever a buffer is unloaded, you can use
the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd BufUnload * let @/ = ""
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help @/\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-@\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help autocmd-searchpat\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help last-pattern\fR
.SS "11.24. Why does this pattern 'a.\e{\-}p\e@!' not match?"
.IX Subsection "11.24. Why does this pattern 'a.{-}p@!' not match?"
\&\*(L"\e{\-}\*(R" doesn't just mean \*(L"as few as possible\*(R", it means \*(L"as few as
possible to make the whole pattern succeed\*(R". If it didn't match the 'p',
the whole pattern would fail (because of the \*(L"p\e@!\*(R") so it does match
the \*(L"p\*(R". It is a longer match, but it is the shortest match that makes
the whole pattern succeed.
.PP
If you wanted \*(L"as few as possible regardless\*(R" you would use \*(L"\e@>\*(R", which
basically divides a pattern up so that the pieces either side behave
independently. If the pattern were \*(L"a.\e{\-}\e@>p\e@!\*(R" then \*(L".\e{\-}\*(R" would
always match nothing because that's the smallest match that can succeed
when there are not other restrictions. The whole pattern then would
behave the same as \*(L"ap\e@!\*(R", i.e. it would match any \*(L"a\*(R" not followed by
a \*(L"p\*(R").
.PP
This means, it matches as few as possible 'a's without trying to keep
going until Vim finds the longest match. This means, it will still match
\&'ap'.
.SS "11.25. How can I use '/' within a pattern, without escaping it?"
.IX Subsection "11.25. How can I use '/' within a pattern, without escaping it?"
When using / to search for a pattern, you need to escape all '/' within
the pattern, because they would otherwise terminate the pattern. So you
can't directly search for /usr/share/doc/ but need to search for
\&\e/usr\e/share\e/doc\e/
.PP
The easiest solution around that, would be to use '?' to start a
backward search and afterwards use /<\s-1CR\s0> to use the last search-pattern
in forward direction.
.PP
If you have a Vim, that has the eval-feature built in (which needs at
least a normal built or higher), you can also directly paste the pattern
into the search register:
.PP
:let @/ = '/usr/share/doc/'
.PP
Then use 'n' to jump to the next occurrence.
.PP
See also the help at
.PP
\&\fB:help @/\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /<\s-1CR\s0\fR>
.SS "11.26. How can I operate on a search match?"
.IX Subsection "11.26. How can I operate on a search match?"
The 'gn' command makes it easy to operate on regions of text that match
the current search pattern. By default, it will search forward for the
last used search pattern and visually select the match. If the cursor is
already on the match, it will be visually selected. If you used the 'gn'
command after an operator (e.g. 'c' to change text), it will be applied
on the match.
.PP
If Visual mode is active before using gn, the visual selection will be
extended until the end of the next match.
.PP
The 'gN' commands works similar but searches backwards.
.PP
This allows to repeat simple operations on each match. For example, you
might want to change each occurence of apples by peaches. So you search
using '/apple' then you can use 'cgnpeach<esc>' to replace the current
match by peach. Now you can use the dot '.' command to redo the
replacement for the rest of the buffer.
.PP
See also the help at
.PP
\&\fB:help gn\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gN\fR
