.SS "12.7. When I yank some text into a register, how do I append the text to the current contents of the register?"
.IX Subsection "12.7. When I yank some text into a register, how do I append the text to the current contents of the register?"
When you specify the register for some operation, if you use the upper-case
for the register name, then the new text will be appended to the existing
contents. For example, if you have some text in the register \*(L"a\*(R". If you
want to append some new text to this, you have to use the \*(L"A\*(R" register
name. If you use the lowercase register name, then the contents of the
register will be overwritten with the new text.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help quote\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quote_alpha\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.1\fR
.SS "12.8. How do I yank a complete sentence that spans over more than one line?"
.IX Subsection "12.8. How do I yank a complete sentence that spans over more than one line?"
To yank a complete sentence that spans over more than one line you have to
use the yank operator followed by a motion command. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&     y)
.Ve
.PP
From inside the sentence you can use 'yi)' to yank the sentence.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help yank\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help {motion}\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help object-motions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 04.6\fR
.SS "12.9. How do I yank all the lines containing a pattern into a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "12.9. How do I yank all the lines containing a pattern into a buffer?"
You can use the \*(L":global\*(R" command to yank all the lines containing the
pattern into a register and then paste the contents of the register into
the buffer:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :let @a=\*(Aq\*(Aq
\& :g/mypattern/y A
.Ve
.PP
The first command, clears the contents of the register \*(L"a\*(R". The second
command copies all the lines containing \*(L"mypattern\*(R" into the register \*(L"a\*(R".
Note that the capital letter \*(L"A\*(R" is used to append the matched lines. Now
you can paste the contents of register \*(L"a\*(R" to a buffer using "ap command.
.PP
If you only want to collect all matches, you can use a different
approach. For that run the ':s' command with the flags 'gn' so that it
won't actually  change the buffer ('n' flag) but select each match ('g'
flag). Combining this with the '\e=' part in the replacement part, you
can copy each match to e.g. a list. Altogether this looks like this:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :let list=[]
\& :%s/pattern/\e=add(list, submatch(0))/gn
.Ve
.PP
Now all matches will be in the list and you can post process them as
wanted.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :g\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :y\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-register\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quote_alpha\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help put\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help registers\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :registers\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help sub\-replace\-\e=\fR
.SS "12.10. How do I delete all the lines in a file that do not contain a pattern?"
.IX Subsection "12.10. How do I delete all the lines in a file that do not contain a pattern?"
You can use \*(L":v\*(R" command to delete all the lines that do not contain a
pattern:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :v/pattern/d
.Ve
.PP
or
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g!/pattern/d
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :v\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :g\fR
.ie n .SS "12.11. How do I add a line before each line with ""pattern"" in it?"
.el .SS "12.11. How do I add a line before each line with ``pattern'' in it?"
.IX Subsection "12.11. How do I add a line before each line with pattern in it?"
You can use the following command to add a line before each line with
\&\*(L"pattern\*(R" in it:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/pattern/normal! Oi<line of text goes here>
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively you can yank the line using the Y command and then insert the
line using the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/pattern/put!
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :g\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :put\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help insert\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 0\fR
.SS "12.12. Is there a way to operate on a line if the previous line contains a particular pattern?"
.IX Subsection "12.12. Is there a way to operate on a line if the previous line contains a particular pattern?"
You can use the \*(L":global\*(R" command to operate on a line, if the previous
line contains a particular pattern:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/<pattern>/+{cmd}
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :g\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :range\fR
.SS "12.13. How do I execute a command on all the lines containing a pattern?"
.IX Subsection "12.13. How do I execute a command on all the lines containing a pattern?"
You can use the \*(L":global\*(R" (:g) command to execute a command on all the
lines containing a pattern.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/my pattern/d
.Ve
.PP
If you want to use a non-Ex command, then you can use the \*(L":normal\*(R"
command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/my pattern/normal {command}
.Ve
.PP
Unless you want the normal mode commands to be remapped, consider using a
\&\*(L":normal!\*(R" command instead (note the \*(L"!\*(R").
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :global\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :v\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :normal\fR
.SS "12.14. Can I copy the character above the cursor to the current cursor position?"
.IX Subsection "12.14. Can I copy the character above the cursor to the current cursor position?"
In Insert mode, you can copy the character above the cursor to the current
cursor position by typing <Ctrl\-Y>. The same can be done with the
characters below the cursor by typing <Ctrl\-E>.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-Y\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-E\fR
.SS "12.15. How do I insert a blank line above/below the current line without entering insert mode?"
.IX Subsection "12.15. How do I insert a blank line above/below the current line without entering insert mode?"
You can use the \*(L":put\*(R" ex command to insert blank lines. For example, try
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :put =\*(Aq\*(Aq
\& :put! =\*(Aq\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :put\fR
.SS "12.16. How do I insert the name of the current file into the current buffer?"
.IX Subsection "12.16. How do I insert the name of the current file into the current buffer?"
There are several ways to insert the name of the current file into the
current buffer. In insert mode, you can use the <C\-R>% or the
<C\-R>=expand(\*(L"%\*(R") command. In normal mode, you can use the \*(L":put =@%\*(R"
command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIexpand()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help !!\fR
.SS "12.17. How do I insert the contents of a Vim register into the current buffer?"
.IX Subsection "12.17. How do I insert the contents of a Vim register into the current buffer?"
In insert mode, you can use the <C\-R><register> command to insert the
contents of <register>. For example, use <C\-R>a to insert the contents
of register \*(L"a\*(R" into the current buffer.
.PP
In normal mode, you can use the \*(L":put <register>\*(R" command to insert the
contents of <register>. For example, use the \*(L":put d\*(R" command to insert
the contents of register \*(L"d\*(R" into the current buffer.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R_CTRL\-P\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :put\fR
.SS "12.18. How do I move the cursor past the end of line and insert some characters at some columns after the end of the line?"
.IX Subsection "12.18. How do I move the cursor past the end of line and insert some characters at some columns after the end of the line?"
You can set the \*(L"virtualedit\*(R" option to move the cursor past the
end-of-line and insert characters in a column after the end-of-line. To
start the virtual mode, use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set virtualedit=all
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'virtualedit'\fR
.ie n .SS "12.19. How to replace the word under the cursor (say: junk) with ""foojunkbar"" in Vim?"
.el .SS "12.19. How to replace the word under the cursor (say: junk) with ``foojunkbar'' in Vim?"
.IX Subsection "12.19. How to replace the word under the cursor (say: junk) with foojunkbar in Vim?"
There are several ways to do this. If the word is the first such word on
the line, use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :exe "s/".expand("<cword>")."/foo&bar/"
.Ve
.PP
To match specifically you could use a more complex substitution like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :exe \*(Aqs/\e<\*(Aq.expand("<cword>").\*(Aq\e%>\*(Aq.(col(".")\-1).\*(Aqc\e>/foo&bar/\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the command: ciwfoo<C\-R>"bar<Esc>
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :substitute\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIexpand()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIcol()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e%c\fR
.SS "12.20. How do I replace a particular text in all the files in a directory?"
.IX Subsection "12.20. How do I replace a particular text in all the files in a directory?"
You can use the \*(L"argdo\*(R" command to execute the substitute command on all
the files specified as arguments:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :args *
\& :argdo %s/<your_text>/<replacement_text>/ge | update
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :args_f\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :argdo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :s_flags\fR
.SS "12.21. I have some numbers in a file. How do I increment or decrement the numbers in the file?"
.IX Subsection "12.21. I have some numbers in a file. How do I increment or decrement the numbers in the file?"
You can use the CTRL-A key to increment the number and the CTRL-X key to
decrement the number. You can also specify the number to
increment/decrement from the number by specifying a count to the key. This
works for decimal, octal and hexadecimal numbers. You can change the base
used by Vim for this operation by modifying the 'nrformats' option.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 26.2\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-A\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-X\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'nrformats'\fR
.ie n .SS "12.22. How do I reuse the last used search pattern in a "":substitute"" command?"
.el .SS "12.22. How do I reuse the last used search pattern in a ``:substitute'' command?"
.IX Subsection "12.22. How do I reuse the last used search pattern in a :substitute command?"
To reuse the last used search pattern in a \*(L":substitute\*(R" command, don't
specify a new search pattern:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :s/pattern/newtext/
\& :s//sometext/
.Ve
.PP
In the second \*(L":s\*(R" command, as a search pattern is not specified, the
pattern specified in the first \*(L":s\*(R" command 'pattern' will be used.
.PP
If you want to change the search pattern but repeat the substitution
pattern you can use the special right hand side, you can use the tilde
character:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :s/newpattern/~/
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :s\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :&\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :~\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help &\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help sub-replace-special\fR
.ie n .SS "12.23. How do I change the case of a string using the "":substitute"" command?"
.el .SS "12.23. How do I change the case of a string using the ``:substitute'' command?"
.IX Subsection "12.23. How do I change the case of a string using the :substitute command?"
You can use special characters in the replacement string for a
\&\*(L":substitute\*(R" command to change the case of the matched string. For
example, to change the case of the string \*(L"MyString\*(R" to all uppercase, you
can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :%s/MyString/\eU&/g
.Ve
.PP
To change the case to lowercase, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :%s/MyString/\eL&/g
.Ve
.PP
To change the case of the first character in all the words in the current
line to uppercase, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :s/\e<\e(.\e)\e(\ek*\e)\e>/\eu\e1\eL\e2/g
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help sub-replace-special\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :substitute\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\eU\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\eL\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\eu\fR
.SS "12.24. How do I enter characters that are not present in the keyboard?"
.IX Subsection "12.24. How do I enter characters that are not present in the keyboard?"
You can use digraphs to enter characters that are not present in the
keyboard. You can use the \*(L":digraphs\*(R" command to display all the currently
defined digraphs. You can add a new digraph to the list using the
\&\*(L":digraphs\*(R" command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help digraphs\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'digraph'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 24.9\fR
.SS "12.25. Is there a command to remove any or all digraphs?"
.IX Subsection "12.25. Is there a command to remove any or all digraphs?"
No. The digraphs table is defined at compile time. You can only add new
ones. Adding a command to remove digraphs is on the todo list.
.SS "12.26. In insert mode, when I press the backspace key, it erases only the characters entered in this instance of insert mode. How do I erase previously entered characters in insert mode using the backspace key?"
.IX Subsection "12.26. In insert mode, when I press the backspace key, it erases only the characters entered in this instance of insert mode. How do I erase previously entered characters in insert mode using the backspace key?"
This is traditional vi behaviour. You can set the 'backspace' option to
erase previously entered characters in insert mode:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set backspace=indent,eol,start
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backspace'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_backspacing\fR
.ie n .SS "12.27. I have a file which has lines longer than 72 characters terminated with ""+"" and wrapped to the next line. How can I quickly join the lines?"
.el .SS "12.27. I have a file which has lines longer than 72 characters terminated with ``+'' and wrapped to the next line. How can I quickly join the lines?"
.IX Subsection "12.27. I have a file which has lines longer than 72 characters terminated with + and wrapped to the next line. How can I quickly join the lines?"
You can use the \*(L":global\*(R" command to search and join the lines:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :g/+$/j
.Ve
.PP
This will, however, only join every second line. A couple of more complex
examples which will join all consecutive lines with a \*(L"+\*(R" at the end are:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :g/*$/,/\e(^\e|[^+]\e)$/j
\& :g/+$/mark a | .,/\e(^\e|[^+]\e)$/s/+$// | \*(Aqa,.j
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :g\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :j\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mark\fR
.SS "12.28. How do I paste characterwise yanked text into separate lines?"
.IX Subsection "12.28. How do I paste characterwise yanked text into separate lines?"
You can use the \*(L":put\*(R" command to paste characterwise yanked text into new
lines:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :put =@"
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :put\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quote_=\fR
.SS "12.29. How do I change the case (uppercase, lowercase) of a word or a character or a block of text?"
.IX Subsection "12.29. How do I change the case (uppercase, lowercase) of a word or a character or a block of text?"
You can use the \*(L"~\*(R" command to switch the case of a character.
.PP
You can change the case of the word under the cursor to uppercase using the
\&\*(L"gUiw\*(R" or \*(L"viwU\*(R" command and to lowercase using the \*(L"guiw\*(R" or \*(L"viwu\*(R"
command.
.PP
You can switch the case (upper case to lower case and vice versa) of the
word under the cursor using the \*(L"viw~\*(R" or \*(L"g~iw\*(R" command.
.PP
You can use the \*(L"gUgU\*(R" command to change the current line to uppercase and
the \*(L"gugu\*(R" command to change the current line to lowercase.
.PP
You can use the \*(L"g~g~\*(R" command to switch the case of the current line. You
can use the \*(L"g~{motion}\*(R" or \*(L"{Visual}~\*(R" commands to switch the case of a
block of text.
.PP
If you set 'tildeop' the \*(L"~\*(R" command behaves like an operator and expects
a motion command to act on. If you have
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set tildeop
.Ve
.PP
and you want to change the case from the current cursor position to the end
of line, simply use \*(L"~$\*(R".
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help case\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'tildeop'\fR
.SS "12.30. How do I enter \s-1ASCII\s0 characters that are not present in the keyboard?"
.IX Subsection "12.30. How do I enter ASCII characters that are not present in the keyboard?"
You can enter \s-1ASCII\s0 characters that are not present in the keyboard by
pressing CTRL-V and then the \s-1ASCII\s0 character number. You can also use
digraphs to enter special \s-1ASCII\s0 characters.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-V_digit\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help digraphs\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 45.5\fR
.SS "12.31. How do I replace non-printable characters in a file?"
.IX Subsection "12.31. How do I replace non-printable characters in a file?"
To replace a non-printable character, you have to first determine the \s-1ASCII\s0
value for the character. You can use the \*(L":ascii\*(R" ex command or the \*(L"ga\*(R"
normal-mode command to display the \s-1ASCII\s0 value of the character under the
cursor.
.PP
You can enter the non-printable character by entering CTRL-V followed by
the decimal number 1\-255 (with no leading zero), or by x and a hex number
00\-FF, or by an octal number 0\-0377 (with leading zero), or by u and a hex
number 0\-FFFF, or by U and a hex number 0\-7FFFFFFF
.PP
Another alternative is to use the \*(L":digraphs\*(R" ex command to display the
digraphs for all characters, together with their value in decimal and
alpha. You can enter a non-printable character by entering CTRL-K followed
by two alphanumeric characters (a digraph).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :ascii\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-V\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-V_digit\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :digraphs\fR
.SS "12.32. How do I remove duplicate lines from a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "12.32. How do I remove duplicate lines from a buffer?"
You can use the following user-defined command to remove all the duplicate
lines from a buffer:
.PP
:command \-range=% Uniq <line1>,<line2>g/^\e%<<line2>l\e(.*\e)\en\e1$/d
.PP
Add the above command to your .vimrc file and invoke \*(L":Uniq\*(R" to remove all
the duplicate lines.
.SS "12.33. How do I prefix all the lines in a file with the corresponding line numbers?"
.IX Subsection "12.33. How do I prefix all the lines in a file with the corresponding line numbers?"
You can prefix the lines in a file with the corresponding line number in
several ways. Some of them are listed below:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& :%s/^/\e=line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq). \*(Aq \*(Aq
\& :%s/^/\e=printf(\*(Aq%5d \*(Aq, line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq))/
\& :%s/^/\e=strpart(line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq).\*(Aq.     \*(Aq, 0, 5)
\& :%s/^/\e=strpart(\*(Aq   \*(Aq, strlen(line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq))).line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq).\*(Aq. \*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
The last two commands will pad the line numbers with space characters.  The
last command will right align the numbers and the command before that will
left align the numbers.
.PP
If you don't want to number consecutive lines but rather non-consecutive
regions, you can also use this idiom:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :let i = 1
\& :g/TODO/s/^/\e=printf(\*(Aq%2d.\*(Aq,i)|let i+=1
.Ve
.PP
This first initializes the variable i with 1. In the next line, a :g
command is used to perform a substitute command only on lines, that
match '\s-1TODO\s0'. After the substitute command has taken place, the variable
i will be incremented by 1.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help sub-replace-special\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIline()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help expr6\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIstrpart()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIprintf()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :execute\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :global\fR
.SS "12.34. How do I exchange (swap) two characters or words or lines?"
.IX Subsection "12.34. How do I exchange (swap) two characters or words or lines?"
You can exchange two characters with the \*(L"xp\*(R" command sequence. The 'x'
will delete the character under the cursor and 'p' will paste the just
deleted character after the character under the cursor. This will result
in exchanging the two characters.
.PP
You can exchange two words with the \*(L"deep\*(R" command sequence (start with the
cursor in the blank space before the first word).
.PP
You can exchange two lines with the \*(L"ddp\*(R" command sequence. The 'dd' will
delete the current line and 'p' will paste the just deleted line after the
current line. This will result in exchanging the two lines.
.PP
All of the above operations will change the " unnamed register.
.PP
You can use the \*(L":m +\*(R" ex command to exchange two lines without changing the
unnamed register.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help x\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help p\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help dd\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help d\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help e\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help linewise-register\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quotequote\fR
.PP
