.SS "14.13. I am seeing a lot of ^M symbols in my file. I tried setting the 'fileformat' option to 'dos' and then 'unix' and then 'mac'. None of these helped. How can I hide these symbols?"
.IX Subsection "14.13. I am seeing a lot of ^M symbols in my file. I tried setting the 'fileformat' option to 'dos' and then 'unix' and then 'mac'. None of these helped. How can I hide these symbols?"
When a file is loaded in Vim, the format of the file is determined as
below:
.PP
\&\- If all the lines end with a new line (<\s-1NL\s0>), then the fileformat is
  'unix'.
\&\- If all the lines end with a carriage return (<\s-1CR\s0>) followed by a new line
  (<\s-1NL\s0>), then the fileformat is 'dos'.
\&\- If all the lines end with carriage return (<\s-1CR\s0>), then the fileformat is
  'mac'.
.PP
If the file has some lines ending with <\s-1CR\s0> and some lines ending with <\s-1CR\s0>
followed by a <\s-1NL\s0>, then the fileformat is set to 'unix'.
.PP
You can change the format of the current file, by saving it explicitly in
dos format:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :w ++ff=dos
.Ve
.PP
To display the format of the current file, use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set fileformat?
.Ve
.PP
The above behavior is also controlled by the 'fileformats' option. You can
try the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& :set fileformats+=unix
\& :e <your_file>
\& :set fileformat=unix
\& :w
.Ve
.PP
To remove the carriage return (<\s-1CR\s0>) character at the end of all the lines
in the current file, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :%s/\er$//
.Ve
.PP
To force Vim to use a particular file format, when editing a file, you can
use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :e ++ff=dos filename
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileformats'\fR
.PP
