.SS "15.7. How do I jump to the beginning/end of a visually selected region?"
.IX Subsection "15.7. How do I jump to the beginning/end of a visually selected region?"
You can use the 'o' command to jump to the beginning/end of a visually
selected region.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help v_o\fR
.SS "15.8. When I select text with mouse and then press : to enter an ex command, the selected text is replaced with the : character. How do I execute an ex command on a text selected using the mouse similar to the text selected using the visual mode?"
.IX Subsection "15.8. When I select text with mouse and then press : to enter an ex command, the selected text is replaced with the : character. How do I execute an ex command on a text selected using the mouse similar to the text selected using the visual mode?"
This will happen if you have configured Vim to use select mode instead of
Visual mode by setting the 'selectmode' option. Check the value of this
option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set selectmode?
.Ve
.PP
This mode is known as selectmode and is similar to the visual mode. This
option is also automatically set when you use the \*(L"behave mswin\*(R" command.
Select mode looks like visual mode, but it is similar to the selection mode
in MS-Windows.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help Select-mode\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'selectmode'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 09.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :behave\fR
.SS "15.9. When I select a block of text using the mouse, Vim goes into selection mode instead of Visual mode. Why?"
.IX Subsection "15.9. When I select a block of text using the mouse, Vim goes into selection mode instead of Visual mode. Why?"
The 'selectmode' option controls whether Select mode will be started when
selecting a block of text using the mouse. To start Visual mode when
selecting text using mouse, remove the 'mouse' value from the 'selectmode'
option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set selectmode\-=mouse
.Ve
.PP
Note that by default, the 'selectmode' option will be set to empty, so that
always visual mode is used.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'selectmode'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Select-mode\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :behave\fR
.SS "15.10. How do I visually select the last copy/pasted text?"
.IX Subsection "15.10. How do I visually select the last copy/pasted text?"
You can use the '[ and '] marks to visually select the last copy/pasted
text. The '[ mark is set to the beginning of the last changed/yanked text
and the '] mark is set to the end of the last changed/yanked text. To
visually select this block of text use the command '[v']
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help '[\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help ']\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help `a\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help v\fR
.SH "COMMAND-LINE MODE"
.IX Header "COMMAND-LINE MODE"
.SS "16.1. How do I use the name of the current file in the command mode or an ex command line?"
.IX Subsection "16.1. How do I use the name of the current file in the command mode or an ex command line?"
In the command line, the '%' character represents the name of the current
file. In some commands, you have to use expand(\*(L"%\*(R") to get the filename:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :!perl %
.Ve
.PP
Another example is to load the latex generated pdf file from the file you
are currently editing:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :!xpdf %<.pdf
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :_%\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help cmdline-special\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIexpand()\fB\fR
.SS "16.2. How do I edit the text in the Vim command-line effectively?"
.IX Subsection "16.2. How do I edit the text in the Vim command-line effectively?"
You can use the command-line window for editing Vim command-line text. To
open the Vim command-line window use the \*(L"q:\*(R" command in normal mode. In
command-line mode, use the CTRL-F key. In this window, the command line
history will be displayed. You can use normal Vim keys/commands to edit any
previous/new command line. To execute a command line, press the
enter/return key.
.PP
In a similar vain, the search history can be edited with \*(L"q/\*(R" and \*(L"q?\*(R"
commands.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help cmdline-window\fR
.SS "16.3. How do I switch from Vi mode to Ex mode?"
.IX Subsection "16.3. How do I switch from Vi mode to Ex mode?"
You can use the Q command to switch from Vi mode to Ex mode. To switch from
Ex mode back to the Vi mode, use the :vi command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help Q\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gQ\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Ex-mode\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :vi\fR
.SS "16.4. How do I copy the output from an ex-command into a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "16.4. How do I copy the output from an ex-command into a buffer?"
To copy the output from an ex-command into a buffer, you have to first get
the command output into a register. You can use the \*(L":redir\*(R" command to get
the output into a register. For example,
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :redir @a
\& :g/HelloWord/p
\& :redir END
.Ve
.PP
Now the register 'a' will contain the output from the ex command
\&\*(L"g/HelloWord/p\*(R". Now you can paste the contents of the register 'a' into a
buffer. You can also send or append the output of an ex-command into a file
using the 'redir' command.
.PP
You can prefix the \*(L":global\*(R" command with \*(L":silent\*(R", to avoid having the
lines printed to the screen.
.PP
To redirect the output from an ex-command to a file, you can use the
following set of commands:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :redir > myfile
\& :g/HelloWord/p
\& :redir END
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :redir\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :silent\fR
.SS "16.5. When I press the tab key to complete the name of a file in the command mode, if there are more than one matching file names, then Vim completes the first matching file name and displays a list of all matching filenames. How do I configure Vim to only display the list of all the matching filenames and not complete the first one?"
.IX Subsection "16.5. When I press the tab key to complete the name of a file in the command mode, if there are more than one matching file names, then Vim completes the first matching file name and displays a list of all matching filenames. How do I configure Vim to only display the list of all the matching filenames and not complete the first one?"
You can modify the 'wildmode' option to configure the way Vim completes
filenames in the command mode. In this case, you can set the 'wildmode'
option to 'list':
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set wildmode=list
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'wildmode'\fR
.SS "16.6. How do I copy text from a buffer to the command line and from the command line to a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "16.6. How do I copy text from a buffer to the command line and from the command line to a buffer?"
To copy text from a buffer to the command line, after yanking the text from
the buffer, use Ctrl-R 0 in the command line to paste the text. You can
also yank the text to a specific register and use CTRL-R <register> to
paste the text to the command line.  You can use CTRL-R CTRL-W to paste the
word under the cursor in the command line.
.PP
To copy text from the command line into a buffer, you can paste the
contents of the : register using the ":p command. The most recently
executed command line is stored in the : register.
.PP
Another approach for copying and pasting text to and from the command line
is to open the command line window using q: from normal mode or CTRL-F from
the command-line mode. In the command line window you can use all the Vim
commands to edit the command line.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help c_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quote_:\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help cmdline-window\fR
.SS "16.7. How do I put a command onto the command history without executing it?"
.IX Subsection "16.7. How do I put a command onto the command history without executing it?"
To put a command onto the command history without executing it, press the
<Esc> key to cancel the command.
.PP
An alternative solution, is to use the \fIhistadd()\fR function like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :call histadd(\*(Aq:\*(Aq, \*(Aqecho strftime("%c")\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help c_<Esc\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIhistadd()\fB\fR
.SS "16.8. How do I increase the height of the command-line?"
.IX Subsection "16.8. How do I increase the height of the command-line?"
You can increase the height of the command-line by changing the 'cmdheight'
option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set cmdheight=2
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cmdheight'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hit-enter\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 05.7\fR
.SH "VIMINFO"
.IX Header "VIMINFO"
.SS "17.1. When I invoke Vim, I get error messages about illegal characters in the viminfo file. What should I do to get rid of these messages?"
.IX Subsection "17.1. When I invoke Vim, I get error messages about illegal characters in the viminfo file. What should I do to get rid of these messages?"
You can remove the \f(CW$HOME\fR/.viminfo or the \f(CW$HOME\fR/_viminfo file to get rid of
these error messages.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help viminfo-errors\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help viminfo-file-name\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help viminfo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 21.3\fR
.SS "17.2. How do I disable the viminfo feature?"
.IX Subsection "17.2. How do I disable the viminfo feature?"
By default, the viminfo feature is disabled. If the viminfo feature is
enabled by a system-wide vimrc file, then you can disable the viminfo
feature by setting the 'viminfo' option to an empty string in your local
\&.vimrc file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set viminfo=""
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viminfo'\fR
.SS "17.3. How do I save and use Vim marks/commands across Vim sessions?"
.IX Subsection "17.3. How do I save and use Vim marks/commands across Vim sessions?"
You can save and restore Vim marks across Vim sessions using the viminfo
file. To use the viminfo file, make sure the 'viminfo' option is not empty.
To save and restore Vim marks, the 'viminfo' option should not contain the
\&'f' flag or should have a value greater than zero for the 'f' option.
.PP
You can also use the viminfo file to synchronize the commandline history
across different sessions using :wvimfo and :rviminfo commands together
with the FocusGained and FocusLost autocommands:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& augroup viminfo
\&     au!
\&     au FocusLost   * wviminfo
\&     au FocusGained * rviminfo
\& augroup end
.Ve
.PP
Note, this will only work reliably, when Vim can detect the FocusLost
and FocusGained autocommands correctly. This means it should work with
GVim but might depend on your terminal for konsole vim.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 21.3\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help viminfo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viminfo'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :wviminfo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :rviminfo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help FocusLost\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help FocusGained\fR
.SH "REMOTE EDITING"
.IX Header "REMOTE EDITING"
.SS "18.1. How do I open a file with existing instance of gvim? What happened to the Vim 5.x OpenWithVim.exe and SendToVim.exe files?"
.IX Subsection "18.1. How do I open a file with existing instance of gvim? What happened to the Vim 5.x OpenWithVim.exe and SendToVim.exe files?"
Starting with Vim6, the \s-1OLE\s0 version of OpenWithVim.exe and SendToVim.exe
Vim utilities are replaced by the new client-server feature. To open the
file j.txt with an existing instance of Gvim (MyVim), use:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ gvim \-\-servername MyVim \-\-remote\-silent j.txt
.Ve
.PP
To list the server names of all the currently running Vim instances, use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-\-serverlist
.Ve
.PP
To get more information about client-server feature, read
.PP
\&\fB:help client-server\fR
.SS "18.2. How do I send a command to a Vim server to write all buffers to disk?"
.IX Subsection "18.2. How do I send a command to a Vim server to write all buffers to disk?"
You can use the Vim remote server functionality to do this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ gvim \-\-servername myVIM \-\-remote\-send "<C\-\e><C\-N>:wall<CR>"
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help client-server\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-\e_CTRL\-N\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :wall\fR
.SS "18.3. Where can I get the documentation about the Vim remote server functionality?"
.IX Subsection "18.3. Where can I get the documentation about the Vim remote server functionality?"
You can get more information about the Vim remote server functionality by
reading
.PP
\&\fB:help client-server\fR
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
.SS "19.1. How do I configure Vim in a simple way?"
.IX Subsection "19.1. How do I configure Vim in a simple way?"
You can use the \*(L":options\*(R" command to open the Vim option window:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :options
.Ve
.PP
This window can be used for viewing and setting all the options.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :options\fR
.SS "19.2. How do I toggle the value of an option?"
.IX Subsection "19.2. How do I toggle the value of an option?"
You can prefix the option with \*(L"inv\*(R" to toggle the value of the option:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set invignorecase
\& :set invhlsearch
.Ve
.PP
You can also suffix the option with \*(L"!\*(R" to toggle the value:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set ignorecase!
\& :set hlsearch!
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help set-option\fR
.SS "19.3. How do I set an option that affects only the current buffer/window?"
.IX Subsection "19.3. How do I set an option that affects only the current buffer/window?"
Some of the Vim options can have a local or global value. A local value
applies only to a specific buffer or window. A global value applies to all
the buffers or windows.
.PP
When a Vim option is modified using the \*(L":set\*(R" command, both the global and
local values for the option are changed. You can use the \*(L":setlocal\*(R"
command to modify only the local value for the option and the \*(L":setglobal\*(R"
command to modify only the global value.
.PP
You can use the \*(L":setlocal\*(R" command to set an option that will affect only
the current file/buffer:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :setlocal textwidth=70
.Ve
.PP
Note that not all options can have a local value. You can use \*(L":setlocal\*(R"
command to set an option locally to a buffer/window only if the option is
allowed to have a local value.
.PP
You can also use the following command to set an option locally:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let &l:{option\-name} = <value>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :setlocal\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help local-options\fR
.SS "19.4. How do I use space characters for a Vim option value?"
.IX Subsection "19.4. How do I use space characters for a Vim option value?"
To use space characters in a Vim option value, you have to escape the space
character. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set tags=tags\e /usr/tags
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help option-backslash\fR
.SS "19.5. Can I add (embed) Vim option settings to the contents of a file?"
.IX Subsection "19.5. Can I add (embed) Vim option settings to the contents of a file?"
You can use modelines to add Vim option settings to the contents of a file.
For example, in a C file, you can add the following line to the top or the
bottom of the file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& /* vim:sw=4: */
.Ve
.PP
This will set the 'shiftwidth' option to 4, when editing that C file.
For this to work, the 'modeline' option should be set. By default, the
\&'modeline' option is set. An alternative example is given in this document
in the first line.
.PP
The 'modelines' settings specifies the number of
lines that will be checked for the Vim set commands.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 21.6\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help modeline\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help auto-setting\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'modeline'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'modelines'\fR
.SS "19.6. How do I display the line numbers of all the lines in a file?"
.IX Subsection "19.6. How do I display the line numbers of all the lines in a file?"
You can set the 'number' option to display the line numbers for all the
lines.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set number
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'number'\fR
.ie n .SS "19.7. How do I change the width of the line numbers displayed using the ""number"" option?"
.el .SS "19.7. How do I change the width of the line numbers displayed using the ``number'' option?"
.IX Subsection "19.7. How do I change the width of the line numbers displayed using the number option?"
You can set the minimum number of columns to be used for line numbering by
setting the 'numberwidth' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set numberwidth=3
.Ve
.PP
This set's the width for the line number to 3 digits, which is enough, if
your buffer contains less than 999 lines. However, if your current buffer
contains more lines than 999, the 'numberwidth' will be adjusted accordingly,
so that the maximum line number will fit on the screen.
.SS "19.8. How do I display (view) all the invisible characters like space, tabs and newlines in a file?"
.IX Subsection "19.8. How do I display (view) all the invisible characters like space, tabs and newlines in a file?"
You can set the 'list' option to see all the invisible characters in your
file.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set list
.Ve
.PP
With this option set, you can view space characters, tabs, newlines,
trailing space characters and wrapped lines.
.PP
To not display the invisible characters (which is the default), you have to
reset the 'list' option:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :set nolist
\& (or)
\& :set list!
.Ve
.PP
The \*(L":set list!\*(R" command will toggle the current setting of the boolean
\&'list' option.
.PP
You can modify the 'listchars' option to configure how and which invisible
characters are displayed. For example, with the following command all the
trailing space characters will be displayed with a '.' character.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set listchars=trail:.
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'listchars'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'list'\fR
.SS "19.9. How do I configure Vim to always display the current line and column number?"
.IX Subsection "19.9. How do I configure Vim to always display the current line and column number?"
You can set the 'ruler' option to display current column and line number in
the status line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set ruler
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ruler'\fR
.SS "19.10. How do I display the current Vim mode?"
.IX Subsection "19.10. How do I display the current Vim mode?"
You can set the 'showmode' option to display the current Vim mode. In
Insert, Replace and Visual modes, Vim will display the current mode on the
last line.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set showmode
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'showmode'\fR
.SS "19.11. How do I configure Vim to show pending/partial commands on the status line?"
.IX Subsection "19.11. How do I configure Vim to show pending/partial commands on the status line?"
You can set the 'showcmd' option to display pending/partial commands in the
status line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set showcmd
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'showcmd'\fR
.SS "19.12. How do I configure the Vim status line to display different settings/values?"
.IX Subsection "19.12. How do I configure the Vim status line to display different settings/values?"
You can set the 'statusline' option to display different values/settings in
the Vim status line.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'statusline'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'laststatus'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'rulerformat'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ruler'\fR
.SS "19.13. How do I configure Vim to display status line always?"
.IX Subsection "19.13. How do I configure Vim to display status line always?"
You can set the 'laststatus' option to 2 to display the status line always.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set laststatus=2
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'laststatus'\fR
.SS "19.14. How do I make a Vim setting persistent across different Vim invocations/instances/sessions?"
.IX Subsection "19.14. How do I make a Vim setting persistent across different Vim invocations/instances/sessions?"
To make a Vim option setting persistent across different Vim instances, add
your setting to the .vimrc or .gvimrc file. You can also use the \*(L":mkvimrc\*(R"
command to generate a vimrc file for the current settings.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help save-settings\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help vimrc\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gvimrc\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help vimrc-intro\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mkvimrc\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help initialization\fR
.SS "19.15. Why do I hear a beep (why does my window flash) about 1 second after I hit the Escape key?"
.IX Subsection "19.15. Why do I hear a beep (why does my window flash) about 1 second after I hit the Escape key?"
This is normal behavior. If your window flashes, then you've got the visual
bell on. Otherwise, you should hear a beep.
.PP
Vim needs a timeout to tell the difference between a simple escape and,
say, a cursor key sequence.  When you press a key in normal mode (and even
in insert mode) and that key is the beginning of a mapping, Vim waits a
certain amount of time to see if the rest of the mapping sequence follows.
If the mapping sequence is completed before a given timeout period, the
mapping for that sequence of keys is applied. If you interrupt the mapping,
the normal actions associated with the keys are executed.
.PP
For example, if you have a mapping defined as \*(L":imap vvv Vim is great!!\*(R"
and you type \*(L"vvv\*(R" quickly, the \*(L"Vim is great!!\*(R" will be inserted into your
text. But if you type \*(L"vv v\*(R" then that is what will put into your text.
This is also true if you type \*(L"vvv\*(R" too slowly where \*(L"too slowly\*(R" is longer
than the value for the timeout option. Setting the timeout option to a
larger value can help alleviate problems that appear when using function
keys over a slow line.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ttimeout'\fR
.SS "19.16. How do I make the 'c' and 's' commands display a '$' instead of deleting the characters I'm changing?"
.IX Subsection "19.16. How do I make the 'c' and 's' commands display a '$' instead of deleting the characters I'm changing?"
To make the 'c' and 's' commands display a '$' instead of deleting the
characters, add the $ flag to the 'cpoptions' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set cpoptions+=$
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cpoptions'\fR
.ie n .SS "19.17. How do I remove more than one flag using a single "":set"" command from a Vim option?"
.el .SS "19.17. How do I remove more than one flag using a single ``:set'' command from a Vim option?"
.IX Subsection "19.17. How do I remove more than one flag using a single :set command from a Vim option?"
You can remove more than one flag from a Vim option using a single \*(L":set\*(R"
command, by specifying the flags in exactly the same order as they appear
in the option. For example, if you use the following command to remove the
\&'t' and 'n' flags from the 'formatoptions' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set formatoptions\-=tn
.Ve
.PP
The 't' and 'n' flags will be removed from the 'formatoptions' option, only
if the 'formatoptions' option contains these flags in this order: 'tn'.
Otherwise, it will not remove the flags. To avoid this problem, you can
remove the flags one by one:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set formatoptions\-=t formatoptions\-=n
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :set\-=\fR
.SH "MAPPING KEYS"
.IX Header "MAPPING KEYS"
.SS "20.1. How do I know what a key is mapped to?"
.IX Subsection "20.1. How do I know what a key is mapped to?"
To see what a key is mapped to, use the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :map <key>
\& :map! <key>
.Ve
.PP
You can also check the mappings in a particular mode using one of the
\&\*(L":cmap\*(R", \*(L":nmap\*(R", \*(L":vmap\*(R", \*(L":imap\*(R", \*(L":omap\*(R", etc commands.
.PP
To find out, where the key has been mapped, prefix the :verbose command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :verbose :map <key>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help map-listing\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help map-overview\fR
.SS "20.2. How do I list all the user-defined key mappings?"
.IX Subsection "20.2. How do I list all the user-defined key mappings?"
You can list all the user-defined key mappings using:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help map-listing\fR
.SS "20.3. How do I unmap a previously mapped key?"
.IX Subsection "20.3. How do I unmap a previously mapped key?"
You can unmap a previously mapped key using the \*(L":unmap\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :unmap <key>
\& :unmap! <key>
.Ve
.PP
For mode specific mappings, you can use one of the
\&\*(L":nunmap/:vunmap/:ounmap/:iunmap/:lunmap/:cunmap\*(R" commands.
.PP
The following command will fail to unmap a buffer-local mapped key:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :unmap <key>
.Ve
.PP
To unmap a buffer-local mapped key, you have to use the <buffer> keyword in
the unmap command:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :unmap <buffer> <key>
\& :unmap! <buffer> <key>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :unmap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help map-modes\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :map\-local\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help mapleader\fR
.SS "20.4. I am not able to create a mapping for the <xxx> key. What is wrong?"
.IX Subsection "20.4. I am not able to create a mapping for the <xxx> key. What is wrong?"
1) First make sure, the key is passed correctly to Vim. To determine if
   this is the case, put Vim in Insert mode and then hit Ctrl-V (or
   Ctrl-Q if your Ctrl-V is remapped to the paste operation (e.g. on
   Windows if you are using the mswin.vim script file) followed by your
   key.
.PP
.Vb 5
\&   If nothing appears in the buffer (and assuming that you have
\&   \*(Aqshowcmd\*(Aq on, ^V remains displayed near the bottom right of the Vim
\&   screen), then Vim doesn\*(Aqt get your key correctly and there is nothing
\&   to be done, other than selecting a different key for your mapping or
\&   using GVim, which should recognise the key correctly.
.Ve
.PP
2) Possibly, Vim gets your key, but sees it as no different than
   something else. Say you want to map Ctrl-Right, then in Insert mode
   hit Ctrl-K followed by Ctrl-Right. If Vim displays <C\-Right> it has
   correctly seen the keystroke and you should be able to map it (by
   using <C\-Right> as your {lhs}). If it displays <Right> it has seen
   the keystroke but as if you hadn't held Ctrl down: this means your
   temrinal passes Ctrl-Right as if it were just <Right>. Anything else
   means the key has been misidentified.
.PP
3) If the key is seen, but not as itself and not as some recognizable
   key, then there is probably an error in the terminal library for the
   current terminal (termcap or terminfo database). In that case
.PP
.Vb 1
\&     :set term?
\&
\&   will tell you which termcap or terminfo Vim is using. You can try to
\&   tell vim, what termcode to use in that terminal, by adding the
\&   following to your vimrc:
\&
\&     if &term == <termname>
\&         set <C\-Right>=<keycode>
\&     endif
\&
\&   where <termname> above should be replaced by the value of \*(Aqterm\*(Aq
\&   (with quotes around it) and <keycode> by what you get when hitting
\&   Ctrl\-V followed by Ctrl\-Right in Insert mode (with nothing around
\&   it). <C\-Right> should be left as\-is (9 characters). Don\*(Aqt forget that
\&   in a :set command, white space is not allowed between the equal sign
\&   and the value, and any space, double quote, vertical bar or backslash
\&   present as part of the value must be backslash\-escaped.
\&
\&   Now you should be able to see the keycode corresponding to the key
\&   and you can create a mapping for the key using the following command:
\&
\&     :map <C\-Right>  <your_command_to_be_mapped>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help map-keys-fails\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :map\-special\-keys\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help key-codes\fR
.SS "20.5. Why does mapping the <C\-...> key not work?"
.IX Subsection "20.5. Why does mapping the <C-...> key not work?"
The only Ctrl-printable-key chords which Vim can reliably detect (because they
are defined in the \s-1ASCII\s0 standard) are the following:
.PP
.Vb 9
\&     Ctrl\-@                 0x00            NUL
\&     Ctrl\-A to Ctrl\-Z       0x01 to 0x1A
\&     Ctrl\-a to Ctrl\-z       0x01 to 0x1A
\&     Ctrl\-[                 0x1B            ESC
\&     Ctrl\-\e                 0x1C
\&     Ctrl\-]                 0x1D
\&     Ctrl\-^                 0x1E
\&     Ctrl\-_                 0x1F
\&     Ctrl\-?                 0x7F            DEL
.Ve
.PP
Most of these, however, already have a function in Vim (and some are
aliases of other keys: Ctrl-H and Bsp, Ctrl-I and Tab, Ctrl-M and Enter,
Ctrl\-[ and Esc, Ctrl\-? and Del).
.PP
The \*(L"safest\*(R" keys to use in Vim for the {lhs} of a mapping are the F
keys, with or without Shift: <F2> to <F12> and <S\-F1> to <S\-F12>. (Some
OSes, including mine, intercept Ctrl-Fn and Alt-Fn, which never reach an
application program such as vim or gvim).
.PP
You can try other combinations of Ctrl + any key, but they may either
not work everywhere (e.g. the terminal might not pass that key to Vim,
or they might have unintended side effects (e.g. mapping <C\-I> means
also to map <Tab>).
.PP
This is a known issue, that has been discussed and might be implemented
in the future to enable Vim to distinguish between various keys even in
console mode. (e.g.
https://groups.google.com/d/msg/vim_dev/2bp9UdfZ63M/sajb9KM0pNYJ)
.SS "20.6. How do I map the numeric keypad keys?"
.IX Subsection "20.6. How do I map the numeric keypad keys?"
First make sure that the numeric keypad keys are passed to Vim. Next, you
can use the following command to map the numeric keypad keys:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <kSomething>  <your_command>
.Ve
.PP
where, <kSomething> can be kHome, kEnd, kPageUp, kPageDown, kPlus, kMinus,
kDivide, kMultiply, kEnter, etc.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help key-codes\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help terminal-options\fR
.SS "20.7. How do I create a mapping that works only in visual mode?"
.IX Subsection "20.7. How do I create a mapping that works only in visual mode?"
You can create mappings that work only in specific modes (normal, command,
insert, visual, etc). To create a mapping that works only in the visual
mode, use the \*(L":vmap\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :vmap <F3> <your mapping here>
.Ve
.PP
This mapping will work in visual and select mode. If you want the map to
work only in visual mode (excluding select mode), use:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :xmap <F3> <your mapping here>
.Ve
.PP
and to have the mapping only work in select mode (but not visual mode),
use:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :smap <F3> <your mapping here>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :vmap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :xmap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :smap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help map-modes\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 40.1\fR
.SS "20.8. How do I create a mapping that works only in normal and operator pending mode (but not in visual mode)?"
.IX Subsection "20.8. How do I create a mapping that works only in normal and operator pending mode (but not in visual mode)?"
Using \*(L":map\*(R" creates a mapping that works in normal, visual+select mode and
operator pending mode. You can use \*(L":nmap\*(R" to have the mapping only work in
normal mode and \*(L":vmap\*(R" to have the mapping only be defined for visual and
select mode or use \*(L":omap\*(R" to have the mapping only defined in operator
pending mode.
.PP
But if you want to have a mapping defined, that works in both operator
pending mode and normal mode, but not in visual and select mode, you need
to first define the mapping using \*(L":map\*(R" and afterwards delete the mapping
for visual and select mode:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        :map <f3> <your mapping here>
\&        :vunmap <f3>
.Ve
.SS "20.9. In a Vim script, how do I know which keys to use for my mappings, so that the mapped key will not collide with an already used key?"
.IX Subsection "20.9. In a Vim script, how do I know which keys to use for my mappings, so that the mapped key will not collide with an already used key?"
Vim uses most of the keys in the keyboard. You can use the <leader> prefix
in maps to define keys which will not overlap with Vim keys. For example:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :map <leader>S <C\-W>s
\& :map <leader>j <C\-W>j
\& :map <leader>k <C\-W>k
.Ve
.PP
where by default <leader> gets substituted with a backslash (\e), so the
user would enter
.PP
.Vb 3
\&     \es
\&     \ej
\&     \ek
.Ve
.PP
to invoke the above map commands. The user can change the mapleader
variable to be whatever they wanted:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let mapleader = ","
.Ve
.PP
When writing a plugin or other script, more often than not, it is advisable
to use :noremap instead of :map to avoid side effects from user defined
mappings.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help <Leader\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help <LocalLeader\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help write-plugin\fR
.SS "20.10. How do I map the escape key?"
.IX Subsection "20.10. How do I map the escape key?"
You can map the Escape key to some other key using the \*(L":map\*(R" command. For
example, the following command maps the escape key to CTRL-O.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <C\-O> <Esc>
.Ve
.SS "20.11. How do I map a key to perform nothing?"
.IX Subsection "20.11. How do I map a key to perform nothing?"
You can map a key to <Nop> to perform nothing when the key is pressed. For
example, with the following mappings, the <F7> key will do nothing when
pressed.
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :map <F7> <Nop>
\& :map! <F7> <Nop>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help <Nop\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help :map\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :map!\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help map-modes\fR
.SS "20.12. I want to use the Tab key to indent a block of text and Shift-Tab key to unindent a block of text. How do I map the keys to do this? This behavior is similar to textpad, visual studio, etc."
.IX Subsection "20.12. I want to use the Tab key to indent a block of text and Shift-Tab key to unindent a block of text. How do I map the keys to do this? This behavior is similar to textpad, visual studio, etc."
Use the following mapping:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& :inoremap <S\-Tab> <C\-O><lt><lt>
\& :nnoremap <Tab> >>
\& :nnoremap <S\-Tab> <lt><lt>
\& :vnoremap <Tab> >
\& :vnoremap <S\-Tab> <lt>
.Ve
.PP
Note, that the <S\-Tab> mapping will work only if Vim receives the correct
key sequence. This is mostly the case with \s-1GUI\s0 Vim.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :inoremap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :nnoremap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :vnoremap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help <S\-Tab\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \fR>>
.PP
\&\fB:help <<\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help <lt\fR>
.SS "20.13. In my mappings the special characters like <\s-1CR\s0> are not recognized. How can I configure Vim to recognize special characters?"
.IX Subsection "20.13. In my mappings the special characters like <CR> are not recognized. How can I configure Vim to recognize special characters?"
Check the value of the 'cpoptions' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set cpoptions?
.Ve
.PP
If this option contains the '<' flag, then special characters will not be
recognized in mappings. Remove the '<' flag from 'cpoptions' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set cpo\-=<
.Ve
.PP
Also, check the value of the 'compatible' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set compatible?
.Ve
.PP
The 'compatible' option must be reset:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nocompatible
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cpoptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'compatible'\fR
.SS "20.14. How do I use the '|' to separate multiple commands in a map?"
.IX Subsection "20.14. How do I use the '|' to separate multiple commands in a map?"
You can escape the '|' character using backslash (\e) to use '|' in a map.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map _l :!ls \e| more<CR>
.Ve
.PP
You can also try the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map _l :!ls <bar> more<CR>
.Ve
.PP
There are also other ways to do this.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help map_bar\fR
.SS "20.15. If I have a mapping/abbreviation whose ending is the beginning of another mapping/abbreviation, how do I keep the first from expanding into the second one?"
.IX Subsection "20.15. If I have a mapping/abbreviation whose ending is the beginning of another mapping/abbreviation, how do I keep the first from expanding into the second one?"
Instead of using the \*(L":map lhs rhs\*(R" command, use the \*(L":noremap lhs rhs\*(R"
command. For abbreviations, use \*(L"noreabbrev lhs rhs\*(R". The \*(L"nore\*(R" prefix
prevents the mapping or abbreviation from being expanded again.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :noremap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :noreabbrev\fR
.SS "20.16. Why does it take a second or more for Vim to process a key, sometimes when I press a key?"
.IX Subsection "20.16. Why does it take a second or more for Vim to process a key, sometimes when I press a key?"
Make sure you have not defined a mapping for this key using the following
command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <key>
.Ve
.PP
If a mapping is defined for this key and the mapped key contains more than
one character, then Vim will wait for the next character to be pressed to
determine whether it is the mapped key or not. For example, if you have
mapped \*(L"ab\*(R", then if you press \*(L"a\*(R", Vim will wait for the next key to be
pressed. If the next key is \*(L"b\*(R", Vim will execute the mapped sequence.
Otherwise, Vim will proceed with the normal processing of \*(L"a\*(R" followed by
the next key. If the 'timeout' option is set (which is the default), then
Vim will timeout after waiting for the period specified with the
\&'timeoutlen' option (default is 1 second).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help map-typing\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'timeoutlen'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ttimeoutlen'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'timeout'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'ttimeout'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help vt100\-cursor\-keys\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help slow-fast-terminal\fR
.SS "20.17. How do I map a key to run an external command using a visually selected text?"
.IX Subsection "20.17. How do I map a key to run an external command using a visually selected text?"
You can the \*(L":vmap\*(R" command to map a key in the visual mode. In the mapped
command sequence, you have to first yank the text. The yanked text is
available in the '\*(L"' register. Now, you can use the contents of this
register to run the external command. For example, to run the external
command \*(R"perldoc" on a visually selected text, you can use the following
mapping:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :vmap <F7> y:!exec "!perldoc \*(Aq" . @" . "\*(Aq"<CR>
.Ve
.PP
If you want the mapping to work in the visual mode, but not with the
highlighted text, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :vmap <F7> :<C\-U>!perldoc <cword><CR>
.Ve
.PP
The above mapping will use the word under the cursor instead of the
highlighted text. Note the use of the <C\-U> before invoking the \*(L"perldoc\*(R"
external command. The <C\-U> is used to erase the range of text selected in
the visual mode and displayed on the command line. If the visual range is
not removed using <C\-U>, then the output from the external command will
replace the visually selected text.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :vmap\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quote_quote\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-register\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help c_CTRL\-U\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :!cmd\fR
.SS "20.18. How do I map the Ctrl-I key while still retaining the functionality of the <Tab> key?"
.IX Subsection "20.18. How do I map the Ctrl-I key while still retaining the functionality of the <Tab> key?"
The Ctrl-I key and the <Tab> key produce the same keycode, so Vim cannot
distinguish between the Ctrl-I and the <Tab> key. When you map the Ctrl-I
key, the <Tab> key is also mapped (and vice versa). The same restriction
applies for the Ctrl\-[ key and the <Esc> key.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help keycodes\fR
.SS "20.19. How do I define a map to accept a count?"
.IX Subsection "20.19. How do I define a map to accept a count?"
Use the @= command to use an expression. For example,
.PP
.Vb 1
\& nnoremap = @=\*(Aq3l\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Now you can specify a count to the '=' command.
.PP
\&\fB:help complex-repeat\fR
.SS "20.20. How can I make my normal mode mapping work from within Insert Mode?"
.IX Subsection "20.20. How can I make my normal mode mapping work from within Insert Mode?"
Mappings in normal mode can be executed after <Ctrl\-O> from insert mode as
well but if there are more commands included in the mapping {rhs}, only the
first one will be executed in normal mode and the rest of {rhs} will be
printed literally in insert mode. One of ways to workaround this problem is
to make {rhs} be one command, via wrapping it to the function. For example:
.PP
.Vb 4
\& function GetFontNameOfFirstChar()
\& normal! 0
\& echo getfontname()
\& endfunction
\&
\& :nmap <F9> :call GetFontNameOfFirstChar()<CR>
.Ve
.PP
A more technical and detailed solution to this problem follows and can
be found at http://groups.google.com/group/vim_dev/msg/75f1f2dfc00908bb
.PP
Not every normal mode-mapping is automatically suitable for execution via
<Ctrl\-O> from within insert mode; you need to explicitly design your mappings
for that purpose.
.PP
The <Ctrl\-O> command allows execution of one normal mode command from
within insert mode, then returns to insert mode. If a normal mode mapping
concatenates multiple normal mode commands, this breaks down in temporary
normal mode and literally inserts the second part of the command into the
buffer instead. To support execution of normal mode mappings from within
insert mode, these strategies can be used:
.PP
1) Instead of concatenating multiple normal mode commands, use one :normal
 mapping:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :nnoremap <silent> zC :<C\-U>normal! zCVzC<CR>
.Ve
.PP
2) Concatenate multiple Ex commands via <Bar> on the rhs:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :nnoremap zC :<C\-U>call MyMap1()<Bar>call MyMap2()<CR>
.Ve
.PP
3) Shadow normal mode mappings by insert mode mappings that
 re-enter normal mode, then invoke the normal mode mapping:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :nnoremap <silent> <SID>MyMap2 :<C\-U>call MyMap2()<CR>
\& :inoremap <silent> <script> <SID>MyMap2 <C\-\e><C\-O><SID>MyMap2
\& :nnoremap <silent> <script> zC <SID>MyMap1<SID>MyMap2
.Ve
.PP
4) Normal mode mappings that consist of multiple Ex command lines (and
 where Ex commands cannot be concatenated via <Bar>) replace ':<C\-U>'
 with <\s-1SID\s0>\s-1NM\s0; the <\s-1SID\s0>\s-1NM\s0 mapping enters normal mode for one ex command
 line:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :nnoremap <silent> <SID>NM :<C\-U>
\& :inoremap <silent> <SID>NM <C\-\e><C\-O>:
\& :nnoremap <silent> <script> zC <SID>MyMap1<SID>NMcall MyMap2()<CR>
.Ve
.PP
5)  If none of the above is possible, at least force normal mode for
 subsequent commands via <CTRL\-\e><\s-1CTRL\-N\s0> to avoid accidental insertion
 of the remainder of the mapping.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :nnoremap zC zC<C\-\e><C\-N>VzCzz
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help map_bar\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-\e_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL\-\e_CTRL\-N\fR
.SH "ABBREVIATIONS"
.IX Header "ABBREVIATIONS"
.SS "21.1. How do I auto correct misspelled words?"
.IX Subsection "21.1. How do I auto correct misspelled words?"
You can auto correct misspelled words using abbreviations. For example, the
following abbreviation can be used to correct \*(L"teh\*(R" with \*(L"the\*(R":
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :abbreviate teh the
.Ve
.PP
Vim supports abbreviations in insert mode, replace mode and command-line
mode.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 24.7\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help abbreviations\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Q_ab\fR
.SS "21.2. How do I create multi-line abbreviations?"
.IX Subsection "21.2. How do I create multi-line abbreviations?"
You can create multi-line abbreviations by embedding the \*(L"<\s-1CR\s0>\*(R"
key code in the text:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& iabbrev #c \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-<CR>\-\- Date:<CR>\-\-<CR>\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
.Ve
.PP
With the above abbreviation, when you type #c, it will be expanded to
the following text:
.PP
\&\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&\*(-- Date:
\&\*(--
\&\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help abbreviations\fR
.SS "21.3. When my abbreviations are expanded, an additional space character is added at the end of the expanded text. How do I avoid this character?"
.IX Subsection "21.3. When my abbreviations are expanded, an additional space character is added at the end of the expanded text. How do I avoid this character?"
To avoid an additional space character at the end of the expanded text, you
can expand the abbreviation by pressing the \s-1CTRL\-\s0] key.  The abbreviation
will be expanded without adding a space character at the end.
.PP
Another alternative is to use the following function and command:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& function! Eatchar(pat)
\&     let c = nr2char(getchar())
\&     return (c =~ a:pat) ? \*(Aq\*(Aq : c
\& endfunction
\& command! \-nargs=+ Iabbr execute "iabbr" <q\-args> . "<C\-R>=Eatchar(\*(Aq\e\es\*(Aq)<CR>"
.Ve
.PP
Now, define your abbreviations using the new \*(L"Iabbr\*(R" command instead of the
builtin \*(L"iabbrev\*(R" command. With this command, after expanding the
abbreviated text, the next typed space character will be discarded.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help abbreviations\fR
.SS "21.4. How do I insert the current date/time stamp into the file?"
.IX Subsection "21.4. How do I insert the current date/time stamp into the file?"
You can use the \fIstrftime()\fR function to insert the current data/time stamp
in a file. For example, you can use the following abbreviation:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& iabbrev dts <C\-R>=strftime("%y/%m/%d %H:%M")<CR>
.Ve
.PP
With this abbreviation, when you type dts in insert mode, it will be
expanded to the date/time stamp.
.PP
Some other forms of the above abbreviation are listed below:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& iabbrev mdyl <C\-R>=strftime("%a %d %b %Y")<CR>
\& iabbrev mdys <C\-R>=strftime("%y%m%d")<CR>
\& iabbrev mdyc <C\-R>=strftime("%c")<CR>
\& iabbrev hml  <C\-R>=strftime("%d/%m/%y %H:%M:%S")<CR>
\& iabbrev hms  <C\-R>=strftime("%H:%M:%S")<CR>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIstrftime()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R\fR
.SS "21.5. How do I prevent an abbreviation from expanding in insert mode?"
.IX Subsection "21.5. How do I prevent an abbreviation from expanding in insert mode?"
You can prevent an abbreviation from expanding in insert mode by typing
CTRL-V before the character after the abbreviated word.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help abbreviations\fR
.SH "RECORD AND PLAYBACK"
.IX Header "RECORD AND PLAYBACK"
.SS "22.1. How do I repeat an editing operation (insertion, deletion, paste, etc)?"
.IX Subsection "22.1. How do I repeat an editing operation (insertion, deletion, paste, etc)?"
You can repeat the last editing operation using the '.' command. This will
repeat the last simple change like a insert, delete, change, paste, etc.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 04.3\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help single-repeat\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Q_re\fR
.SS "22.2. How I record and repeat a set of key sequences?"
.IX Subsection "22.2. How I record and repeat a set of key sequences?"
You can use the 'q' command in normal mode to record a set of key sequences
and store it in a register. For example, in the normal mode you can press q
followed by a register name {0\-9a\-bA\-Z"} to start the recording.  To
end/stop the recording press q again. You can playback/repeat the recorded
key sequences by pressing @ followed by the register name. e.g. \f(CW@a\fR.
.PP
Another approach is to start Vim with the \*(L"\-w\*(R" command-line argument.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-w <file_name>
.Ve
.PP
Vim will record all the characters typed in the session in the
specified file \*(L"file_name\*(R". You can use the recorded file with the \*(L"\-s\*(R"
command line argument to play it back:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-s <file_name>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.1\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help recording\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-w\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-s\fR
.SS "22.3. How do I edit/modify a recorded set of key sequences?"
.IX Subsection "22.3. How do I edit/modify a recorded set of key sequences?"
The recorded key sequences are stored in a register. You can paste the
contents of the register into a Vim buffer, edit the pasted text and again
yank the text into the register. You can also use the \*(L":let\*(R" command to
modify the register. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let @a = "iHello World\e<Esc>"
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help recording\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.1\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-register\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help <\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cpoptions'\fR
.SS "22.4. How do I write recorded key sequences to a file?"
.IX Subsection "22.4. How do I write recorded key sequences to a file?"
The recorded key sequences are stored in a register. You can paste the
contents of the register into a Vim buffer. Now you can save the buffer
into a file. You can also modify the pasted text and again yank into the
register to modify the recorded key sequence. For example, if you record a
set of key sequences using qa ..... q. The recorded key sequences are
stored in the register 'a'. You can paste the contents of register 'a'
using "ap.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help recording\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.1\fR
.SS "22.5. I am using register 0 to record my key sequences (i.e. q0 .... q). In the recorded key sequences, I am yanking some text. After the first replay of the recorded key sequence, I am no longer able to play it back."
.IX Subsection "22.5. I am using register 0 to record my key sequences (i.e. q0 .... q). In the recorded key sequences, I am yanking some text. After the first replay of the recorded key sequence, I am no longer able to play it back."
Register 0 contains the text from the last yank operation. In your recorded
key sequence, when the yank is performed, register 0 is overwritten with
the yanked text. So your recording stored in register 0 is lost. You have
to use some other register.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help registers\fR
.SH "AUTOCOMMANDS"
.IX Header "AUTOCOMMANDS"
.SS "23.1. How do I execute a command when I try to modify a read-only file?"
.IX Subsection "23.1. How do I execute a command when I try to modify a read-only file?"
You can use the FileChangedRO autocommand event to execute a command when a
read-only file is modified. For example, you can use this event to checkout a
read-only file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd FileChangedRO * call MyCheckoutFunction()
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help FileChangedRO\fR
.SS "23.2. How do I execute a command every time when entering a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "23.2. How do I execute a command every time when entering a buffer?"
You can use the BufEnter autocommand event to execute a command every time
when entering a buffer. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd BufEnter *.c set formatoptions=croqt
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help BufEnter\fR
.SS "23.3. How do I execute a command every time when entering a window?"
.IX Subsection "23.3. How do I execute a command every time when entering a window?"
You can use the WinEnter autocommand event to execute a command every time
when entering a window. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd WinEnter *.c call MyFunction()
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help WinEnter\fR
.SS "23.4. From an autocmd, how can I determine the name of the file or the buffer number for which the autocommand is executed?"
.IX Subsection "23.4. From an autocmd, how can I determine the name of the file or the buffer number for which the autocommand is executed?"
You can use the special words <afile> or <abuf> in an autocmd to get the
name of the file or the buffer number for which the autocommand is
executed.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :<afile\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help :<abuf\fR>
.PP
\&\fB:help :<amatch\fR>
.SS "23.5. How do I automatically save all the changed buffers whenever Vim loses focus?"
.IX Subsection "23.5. How do I automatically save all the changed buffers whenever Vim loses focus?"
You can define an autocommand for the FocusLost event which will save all
the modified buffers whenever Vim loses focus:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd FocusLost * wall
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help FocusLost\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :wall\fR
.SS "23.6. How do I execute/run a function when Vim exits to do some cleanup?"
.IX Subsection "23.6. How do I execute/run a function when Vim exits to do some cleanup?"
You can use VimLeave autocmd event to execute a function just before Vim
exits. For example,
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :autocmd VimLeave * call MyCleanupFunction()
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help VimLeave\fR
.SH "SYNTAX HIGHLIGHT"
.IX Header "SYNTAX HIGHLIGHT"
.SS "24.1. How do I turn off/on syntax highlighting?"
.IX Subsection "24.1. How do I turn off/on syntax highlighting?"
By default, the Vim syntax highlighting is turned off. To enable the syntax
highlighting, you can use one of the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :syntax enable
\&
\& or
\&
\& :syntax on
.Ve
.PP
To disable the syntax highlighting, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :syntax off
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 06.1\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 06.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :syntax\-enable\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :syntax\-on\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :syn\-clear\fR
.SS "24.2. How do I change the background and foreground colors used by Vim?"
.IX Subsection "24.2. How do I change the background and foreground colors used by Vim?"
Vim uses the \*(L"Normal\*(R" highlight group for the background and foreground
colors. To change the foreground/background colors, you have to modify the
\&\*(L"Normal\*(R" highlight group. For example, to set the background color to blue
and foreground color to white, you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :highlight Normal ctermbg=blue ctermfg=white guibg=blue guifg=white
.Ve
.PP
If you are using the Motif or the Athena version of the \s-1GUI\s0 Vim, then you
can modify the foreground and background resource names in the .Xdefaults
files to change the colors:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& Vim.foreground:     Black
\& Vim.backround:      Wheat
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L"\-foreground\*(R" and \*(L"\-background\*(R" command-line arguments
to specify the foreground and background colors. These arguments are
supported only in the Motif or Athena versions:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ gvim \-foreground Black \-background Wheat
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :highlight\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help .Xdefaults\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-gui\fR
.SS "24.3. How do I change the highlight colors to suit a dark/light background?"
.IX Subsection "24.3. How do I change the highlight colors to suit a dark/light background?"
You can set the 'background' option to either 'dark' or 'light' to change
the highlight colors to suit a dark/light background:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set background=dark
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'background'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 06.2\fR
.ie n .SS "24.4. How do I change the color of the line numbers displayed when the "":set number"" command is used?"
.el .SS "24.4. How do I change the color of the line numbers displayed when the ``:set number'' command is used?"
.IX Subsection "24.4. How do I change the color of the line numbers displayed when the :set number command is used?"
The line numbers displayed use the LineNr highlighting group. To display
the current colors used, use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :hi LineNr
.Ve
.PP
To change the color modify the LineNr highlight group. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :hi linenr guifg=red guibg=black
.Ve
.PP
This will give red numbers on a black background in \s-1GVIM.\s0
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :highlight\fR
.SS "24.5. How do I change the background color used for a Visually selected block?"
.IX Subsection "24.5. How do I change the background color used for a Visually selected block?"
You can modify the 'Visual' highlight group to change the color used for a
visually selected block:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :highlight Visual guibg=red
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :highlight\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hl-Visual\fR
.SS "24.6. How do I highlight the special characters (tabs, trailing spaces, end of line, etc) displayed by the 'list' option?"
.IX Subsection "24.6. How do I highlight the special characters (tabs, trailing spaces, end of line, etc) displayed by the 'list' option?"
You can modify the \*(L"NonText\*(R" and \*(L"SpecialKey\*(R" highlight groups to highlight
the special characters displayed by the 'list' option:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :highlight NonText guibg=red
\& :highlight SpecialKey guibg=green
.Ve
.PP
The \*(L"NonText\*(R" highlighting group is used for \*(L"eol\*(R", \*(L"extends\*(R" and
\&\*(L"precedes\*(R" settings in the \*(L"listchars\*(R" option.  The \*(L"SpecialKey\*(R"
highlighting group is used for the \*(L"tab\*(R" and \*(L"trail\*(R" settings.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'listchars'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hl-NonText\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hl-SpecialKey\fR
.SS "24.7. How do I specify a colorscheme in my .vimrc/.gvimrc file, so that Vim uses the specified colorscheme every time?"
.IX Subsection "24.7. How do I specify a colorscheme in my .vimrc/.gvimrc file, so that Vim uses the specified colorscheme every time?"
You can specify the color scheme using the \*(L":colorscheme\*(R" command in your
\&.vimrc or .gvimrc file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& colorscheme evening
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :colorscheme\fR
.SS "24.8. Vim syntax highlighting is broken. When I am editing a file, some parts of the file is not syntax highlighted or syntax highlighted incorrectly."
.IX Subsection "24.8. Vim syntax highlighting is broken. When I am editing a file, some parts of the file is not syntax highlighted or syntax highlighted incorrectly."
Vim doesn't read the whole file to parse the text for syntax highlighting.
It starts parsing wherever you are viewing the file. That saves a lot of
time, but sometimes the colors are wrong. A simple fix is refreshing the
screen using the CTRL-L key. Or scroll back a bit and then forward again.
You can also use the command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :syntax sync fromstart
.Ve
.PP
Note that this might considerably slow down the screen refreshing.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :syn\-sync\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :syn\-sync\-first\fR
.SS "24.9. Is there a built-in function to syntax-highlight the corresponding matching bracket?"
.IX Subsection "24.9. Is there a built-in function to syntax-highlight the corresponding matching bracket?"
Yes. Vim includes the matchparen Plugin as standard plugin that is enabled
by default. Whenever the cursor moves over an item defined with the
\&'matchpairs' option, Vim will highlight the corresponding bracket using the
MatchParen highlighting group.
.PP
However, if the corresponding parenthesis is not visible in the current
window, the cursor won't jump to it.
.PP
The matchit plugin provides a similar function, that lets the cursor
jump to related items (e.g. \*(L"if\*(R", \*(L"else\*(R", \*(L"endif\*(R" items) and skips
matches in comments. This uses the % command to jump to corresponding
items. Though both plugins provide similar functions they are unrelated
and work differently.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help matchparen\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'matchpairs'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help matchit-install\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help matchit-intro\fR
.SS "24.10. How do I turn off the C comment syntax highlighting?"
.IX Subsection "24.10. How do I turn off the C comment syntax highlighting?"
You can use the following command to turn off C comment syntax
highlighting:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :highlight clear comment
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help ft-c-syntax\fR
.SS "24.11. How do I add my own syntax extensions to the standard syntax files supplied with Vim?"
.IX Subsection "24.11. How do I add my own syntax extensions to the standard syntax files supplied with Vim?"
You should not modify the syntax files supplied with Vim to add your
extensions. When you install the next version of Vim, you will lose your
changes. Instead you should create a file under the ~/.vim/after/syntax
directory with the same name as the original syntax file and add your
additions to this file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help mysyntaxfile-add\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'runtimepath'\fR
.SS "24.12. How do I replace a standard syntax file that comes with the Vim distribution with my own syntax file?"
.IX Subsection "24.12. How do I replace a standard syntax file that comes with the Vim distribution with my own syntax file?"
You can replace a standard syntax file that comes with the Vim distribution
by creating a file with the same name as the original syntax file and
placing it in the vim runtime syntax (~/.vim/syntax) directory. For
example, to replace the c.vim syntax file in a Unix system, place the new
c.vim in the ~/.vim/syntax directory. In a MS-Windows system, place the new
syntax file in the \f(CW$HOME\fR/vimfiles/syntax or \f(CW$VIM\fR/vimfiles/syntax directory.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help mysyntaxfile-replace\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 44.11\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help mysyntaxfile\fR
.SS "24.13. How do I highlight all the characters after a particular column?"
.IX Subsection "24.13. How do I highlight all the characters after a particular column?"
You can use the \*(L":match\*(R" command to highlight all the characters after a
particular column:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :match Todo \*(Aq\e%>75v.\e+\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
This will highlight all the characters after the 75th column.
.PP
You can also set the 'colorcolumn' option to highlight a particular
column:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   :set colorcolumn=+2
.Ve
.PP
which highlights 2 columns after the current 'textwidth' setting
(alternatively, you can use the exact column number).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :match\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e%v\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /\e+\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help /.\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'colorcolumn'\fR
.SS "24.14. How do I convert a source file (.c, .h, etc) with the Vim syntax highlighting into a \s-1HTML\s0 file?"
.IX Subsection "24.14. How do I convert a source file (.c, .h, etc) with the Vim syntax highlighting into a HTML file?"
You can use the 2html.vim script to convert a source file into a \s-1HTML\s0 file
with the Vim syntax highlighting. Use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :TOhtml
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help convert-to-HTML\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :TOhtml\fR
.SS "24.15. How do I list the definition of all the current highlight groups?"
.IX Subsection "24.15. How do I list the definition of all the current highlight groups?"
You can list the definition of all the current highlight groups using the
\&\*(L":highlight\*(R" (without any arguments) ex command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :highlight\fR
.SS "24.16. How can I embed one syntax highlighting language into another one?"
.IX Subsection "24.16. How can I embed one syntax highlighting language into another one?"
It is possible to include one syntax highlighting into another one,
however most of the currently deployed syntax highlighting scripts are
not prepared to be included into another syntax script.
.PP
You can however create your own custom script to define your own
regions, which will be highlighted with a different language.
.PP
See the wiki for a comprehensive solution:
http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Different_syntax_highlighting_within_regions_of_a_file
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :syn\-include\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help sh-awk\fR
.SH "VIM SCRIPT WRITING"
.IX Header "VIM SCRIPT WRITING"
.SS "25.1. How do I list the names of all the scripts sourced by Vim?"
.IX Subsection "25.1. How do I list the names of all the scripts sourced by Vim?"
You can use the \*(L":scriptnames\*(R" command to list the names of all the scripts
sourced by Vim:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :scriptnames
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :scriptnames\fR
.SS "25.2. How do I debug Vim scripts?"
.IX Subsection "25.2. How do I debug Vim scripts?"
Vim has built-in support for a primitive debugger to debug Vim plugins and
scripts. Using this debugger you can set breakpoints and step through the
plugin functions.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help debug-scripts\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-D\fR
.SS "25.3. How do I locate the script/plugin which sets a Vim option?"
.IX Subsection "25.3. How do I locate the script/plugin which sets a Vim option?"
You can use the \*(L":verbose\*(R" command to locate the plugin/script which last
modified a Vim option. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :verbose set textwidth?
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :set\-verbose\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :verbose\fR
.SS "25.4. I am getting some error/informational messages from Vim (possibly when running a script), the messages are cleared immediately. How do I display the messages again?"
.IX Subsection "25.4. I am getting some error/informational messages from Vim (possibly when running a script), the messages are cleared immediately. How do I display the messages again?"
You can use the \*(L":messages\*(R" command to display the previous messages.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :messages
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :messages\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :echoerr\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :echomsg\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help message-history\fR
.SS "25.5. How do I save and restore a plugin specific information across Vim invocations?"
.IX Subsection "25.5. How do I save and restore a plugin specific information across Vim invocations?"
Vim will save and restore global variables that start with an uppercase
letter and don't contain a lower case letter. For this to work, the
\&'viminfo' option must contain the '!' flag. Vim will store the variables in
the viminfo file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viminfo'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help viminfo-file\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help variables\fR
.SS "25.6. How do I start insert mode from a Vim function?"
.IX Subsection "25.6. How do I start insert mode from a Vim function?"
You can use the \*(L":startinsert\*(R" command to start the insert mode from inside
a Vim function.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :startinsert\fR
.SS "25.7. How do I change the cursor position from within a Vim function?"
.IX Subsection "25.7. How do I change the cursor position from within a Vim function?"
You can use the \fIcursor()\fR function to position the cursor.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&     call cursor(lnum, col)
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively, use the \fIsetpos()\fR function:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    call setpos(\*(Aq.\*(Aq, [bufnum, lnum, col, off])
.Ve
.PP
which set's the cursor in the buffer bufnum to line lnum, column col and
offset for 'virtualedit'. You can use the \fIgetpos()\fR function, to return a
list with these values, that can then be fed back to the \fIsetpos()\fR function.
.PP
If you want to save and restore the viewpoint on a window, use the
\&\fIwinsaveview()\fR and \fIwinrestview()\fR function calls.
.PP
You can also use the following command to change the cursor position:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&     exe "normal! " . lnum . "G" . col . "|"
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIcursor()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help bar\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIgetpos()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIsetpos()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIwinsaveview()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIwinrestview()\fB\fR
.SS "25.8. How do I check the value of an environment variable in the .vimrc file?"
.IX Subsection "25.8. How do I check the value of an environment variable in the .vimrc file?"
You can use prefix the environment variable name with the '$' character to
use it from a Vim script/function.  You can refer to the value of an
environment variable using the \f(CW$env_var\fR syntax:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& if $EDITOR == \*(Aqvi\*(Aq
\& endif
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help expr-env\fR
.SS "25.9. How do I check whether an environment variable is set or not from a Vim function?"
.IX Subsection "25.9. How do I check whether an environment variable is set or not from a Vim function?"
You can use the \fIexists()\fR function to check for the existence of an
environment variable.
.PP
.Vb 2
\& if exists("$MY_ENV_VAR")
\& endif
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIexists()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help expr-env\fR
.SS "25.10. How do I call/use the Vim built-in functions?"
.IX Subsection "25.10. How do I call/use the Vim built-in functions?"
You can use the \*(L":call\*(R" command to invoke a Vim built-in function:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :call cursor(10,20)
.Ve
.PP
You can use the \*(L":echo\*(R" command to echo the value returned by a function:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :echo char2nr(\*(Aqa\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
You can use the \*(L":let\*(R" command to assign the value returned by a function
to a variable:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let a = getline(\*(Aq.\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
To store the return value from a function into a Vim register, you can use
the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let @a = system(\*(Aqls\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
The above command will store the return value from the 'ls' command into
the register 'a'.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :call\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :echo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-register\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help user-functions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help usr_41.txt\fR
.SS "25.11. I am using some normal mode commands in my Vim script. How do I avoid using the user-defined mappings for these normal mode commands and use the standard Vim functionality for these normal mode commands?"
.IX Subsection "25.11. I am using some normal mode commands in my Vim script. How do I avoid using the user-defined mappings for these normal mode commands and use the standard Vim functionality for these normal mode commands?"
You can use the \*(L"normal!\*(R" command in your script to invoke a normal-mode
command. This will use the standard functionality of the normal mode
command and will not use the user-defined mapping.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :normal\fR
.SS "25.12. How do I get the current visually selected text into a Vim variable or register?"
.IX Subsection "25.12. How do I get the current visually selected text into a Vim variable or register?"
You can get the current visually selected text into a Vim variable by
yanking the text into Vim register and then assigning the contents of the
register into the variable:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :normal! gvy
\& :let myvar = @"
.Ve
.PP
The above command copies the visually selected text into the variable
\&\*(L"myvar\*(R".
.PP
You can also use the command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :normal! gv"*y
.Ve
.PP
In the above command, gv reselects the last visually selected text and the
rest of the command copies the selected text into the * (clipboard)
register. Alternatively, you can set the 'a' flag in the 'guioptions'
option to automatically copy a visually selected text into the * register.
To do this as part of a visual map, you can use a command similar to the
one shown below:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :vmap <F3> "*y:call ...
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gv\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :normal\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-@\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quotestar\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help clipboard\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help registers\fR
.ie n .SS "25.13. I have some text in a Vim variable 'myvar'. I would like to use this variable in a "":s"" substitute command to replace a text 'mytext'. How do I do this?"
.el .SS "25.13. I have some text in a Vim variable 'myvar'. I would like to use this variable in a ``:s'' substitute command to replace a text 'mytext'. How do I do this?"
.IX Subsection "25.13. I have some text in a Vim variable 'myvar'. I would like to use this variable in a :s substitute command to replace a text 'mytext'. How do I do this?"
You can use the 'execute' command to evaluate the variable:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :execute \*(Aq%s/mytext/\*(Aq . myvar . \*(Aq/\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :execute\fR
.PP
You can also use \*(L"\e=\*(R" in the substitute command to evaluate the variable:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :%s/mytext/\e=myvar/
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help sub-replace-special\fR
.SS "25.14. A Vim variable (bno) contains a buffer number. How do I use this variable to open the corresponding buffer?"
.IX Subsection "25.14. A Vim variable (bno) contains a buffer number. How do I use this variable to open the corresponding buffer?"
The :buffer command will not accept a variable name. It accepts only a
buffer number or buffer name. You have to use the \*(L":execute\*(R" command to
evaluate the variable into the corresponding value. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :execute "buffer " . bno
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :execute\fR
.SS "25.15. How do I store the value of a Vim option into a Vim variable?"
.IX Subsection "25.15. How do I store the value of a Vim option into a Vim variable?"
You can prefix the option name with the '&' character and assign the option
value to a Vim variable using the \*(L"let\*(R" command. For example, to store the
value of the 'textwidth' option into the Vim variable \*(L"old_tw\*(R", you can use
the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let old_tw = &tw
.Ve
.PP
To explicitly save buffer local options, use the prefix \*(L"l:\*(R"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let old_tw = &l:tw
.Ve
.PP
If you want to explicitly select the global option, use the \*(L"g:\*(R" prefix to
the option name.
.PP
To do the opposite, to set the 'textwidth' option with the value stored in
the 'old_tw' variable, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let &tw = old_tw
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help expr-option\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :let\-option\fR
.SS "25.16. I have copied and inserted some text into a buffer from a Vim function. How do I indent the inserted text from the Vim function?"
.IX Subsection "25.16. I have copied and inserted some text into a buffer from a Vim function. How do I indent the inserted text from the Vim function?"
You can use the following command to format the just inserted text:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :normal \*(Aq[=\*(Aq]
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help '[\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help ']\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help =\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :normal\fR
.SS "25.17. How do I get the character under the cursor from a Vim script?"
.IX Subsection "25.17. How do I get the character under the cursor from a Vim script?"
You can use the \fIgetline()\fR function and use string index [] to get the
character:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :echo getline(".")[col(".") \- 1]
.Ve
.PP
In the above command, getline(\*(L".\*(R") returns  the text in the current line.
The indexing of the string starts at zero, and you can get a single
character in a string by its index with the \*(L"string[index]\*(R" notation. The
col(\*(L".\*(R") returns the column of the cursor position; the adjustment is to
get the right character of the string. However, this does \s-1NOT\s0 work with
multibyte characters as this command only returns the byte index.
.PP
Alternatively, you can use the following sequence of commands to get the
character under the cursor:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& normal! vy
\& let ch=@"
.Ve
.PP
Note, that the above commands will change the '< and '> marks.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIgetline()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIcol()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help expr\-[]\fR
.SS "25.18. How do I get the name of the current file without the extension?"
.IX Subsection "25.18. How do I get the name of the current file without the extension?"
You can get the name of the current file without the extension using:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :echo expand("%:r")
.Ve
.PP
With some commands, you can use the file name modifiers directly:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :cd %:p:h
\& :!gcc \-o %:r.o %
\& :!xpdf %<.pdf
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help filename-modifiers\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIexpand()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help cmdline-special\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIfnamemodify()\fB\fR
.SS "25.19. How do I get the basename of the current file?"
.IX Subsection "25.19. How do I get the basename of the current file?"
You can use the :t filename modifier to get the basename of the current
file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :echo expand("%:t")
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help filename-modifiers\fR
.SS "25.20. How do I get the output from a Vim function into the current buffer?"
.IX Subsection "25.20. How do I get the output from a Vim function into the current buffer?"
You can insert the return value from a function using the following command
in insert mode:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& <C\-R>=MyFunc()
.Ve
.PP
Note, that this will only insert the return value of the function.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R_CTRL\-R\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-R_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help expression\fR
.SS "25.21. How do I call external programs from a Vim function?"
.IX Subsection "25.21. How do I call external programs from a Vim function?"
There are several ways to call external programs from a Vim function. You
can use the builtin \fIsystem()\fR function to invoke external programs and get
the result:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :let output = system("ls")
.Ve
.PP
You can also use \*(L"!\*(R" ex-command to run an external command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(BIsystem()\fB\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :!\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.9\fR
.ie n .SS "25.22. How do I get the return status of a program executed using the "":!"" command?"
.el .SS "25.22. How do I get the return status of a program executed using the ``:!'' command?"
.IX Subsection "25.22. How do I get the return status of a program executed using the :! command?"
You can use the predefined Vim v:shell_error variable to get the return
status of the last run shell command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help v:shell_error\fR
.SS "25.23. How do I determine whether the current buffer is modified or not?"
.IX Subsection "25.23. How do I determine whether the current buffer is modified or not?"
You can check the value of the 'modified' option to determine whether the
current buffer is modified:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set modified?
.Ve
.PP
From a Vim script, you can check the value of the 'modified' option:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& if &modified
\&     echo "File is modified"
\& endif
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'modified'\fR
.SS "25.24. I would like to use the carriage return character in a normal command from a Vim script. How do I specify the carriage return character?"
.IX Subsection "25.24. I would like to use the carriage return character in a normal command from a Vim script. How do I specify the carriage return character?"
You can use the \*(L":execute\*(R" command to specify the special (control)
character in a normal mode command:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :execute "normal \e<CR>"
\& :execute "normal ixxx\e<Esc>"
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :execute\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help expr-quote\fR
.SS "25.25. How do I split long lines in a Vim script?"
.IX Subsection "25.25. How do I split long lines in a Vim script?"
You can split long lines in a Vim script by inserting the backslash
character (\*(L"\e\*(R") at the start of the next line. For example,
