.PP
\&\fB:help line-continuation\fR
.ie n .SS "25.26. When I try to ""execute"" my function using the ""execute 'echo \fIMyfunc()\fP'"" command, the cursor is moved to the top of the current buffer.  Why?"
.el .SS "25.26. When I try to ``execute'' my function using the ``execute 'echo \fIMyfunc()\fP''' command, the cursor is moved to the top of the current buffer.  Why?"
.IX Subsection "25.26. When I try to execute my function using the execute 'echo Myfunc()' command, the cursor is moved to the top of the current buffer. Why?"
The \*(L":execute\*(R" command runs the normal mode command specified by the
argument. In the case of the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :execute "echo Myfunc()"
.Ve
.PP
The call to \*(L"echo \fIMyfunc()\fR\*(R" will return 0. The \*(L":execute\*(R" command will run
the normal mode command \*(L"0\*(R", which moves the cursor to the top of the file.
To call a Vim function, you should use the \*(L":call\*(R" command instead of the
\&\*(L":execute\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :call Myfunc()
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :call\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :execute\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :echo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help user-functions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 41.5\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 41.6\fR
.SS "25.27. How do I source/execute the contents of a register?"
.IX Subsection "25.27. How do I source/execute the contents of a register?"
If you have yanked a set of Vim commands into a Vim register (for example
register 'a'), then you can source the contents of the register using one
of the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :@a
\&or
\& :exe @a
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :@\fR
.SS "25.28. After calling a Vim function or a mapping, when I press the 'u' key to undo the last change, Vim undoes all the changes made by the mapping/function. Why?"
.IX Subsection "25.28. After calling a Vim function or a mapping, when I press the 'u' key to undo the last change, Vim undoes all the changes made by the mapping/function. Why?"
When you call a function or a mapping, all the operations performed by the
function/mapping are treated as one single operation. When you undo the
last operation by pressing 'u', all the changes made by the
function/mapping are reversed.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help undo-redo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :map\-undo\fR
.SS "25.29. How can I call a function defined with s: (script local function) from another script/plugin?"
.IX Subsection "25.29. How can I call a function defined with s: (script local function) from another script/plugin?"
The s: prefix for a Vim function name is used to create a script local
function. A script local function can be called only from within that
script and cannot be called from other scripts. To define a function in a
script/plugin, so that it can be called from other plugins/scripts, define
the function without the s: prefix.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help script-variable\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help script-local\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :scriptnames\fR
.SS "25.30. Is it possible to un-source a sourced script? In other words, reverse all the commands executed by sourcing a script."
.IX Subsection "25.30. Is it possible to un-source a sourced script? In other words, reverse all the commands executed by sourcing a script."
No. It is not possible to reverse or undo all the commands executed by
sourcing a script.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :source\fR
.SH "PLUGINS"
.IX Header "PLUGINS"
.SS "26.1. How do I set different options for different types of files?"
.IX Subsection "26.1. How do I set different options for different types of files?"
You can create filetype plugins to set different options for different
types of files. You should first enable filetype plugins using the command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :filetype plugin on
.Ve
.PP
A filetype plugin is a vim script that is loaded whenever Vim opens or
creates a file of that type.  For example, to ensure that the 'textwidth'
option is set to 80 when editing a C program (filetype 'c'), create one of
the following files:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&     ~/.vim/ftplugin/c.vim (Unix)
\&     %HOME%\evimfiles\eftplugin\ec.vim (Windows)
.Ve
.PP
with the following text in it:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&     setlocal textwidth=80
.Ve
.PP
You can also use autocommands to set specific options when editing specific
type of files. For example, to set the 'textwidth' option to 75 for only
*.txt files, you can use the following autocmd:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& autocmd BufRead *.txt setlocal textwidth=80
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help filetype-plugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help add-filetype-plugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :autocmd\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 40.3\fR
.SS "26.2. I have downloaded a Vim plugin or a syntax file or a indent file, or a color scheme or a filetype plugin from the web. Where should I copy these files so that Vim will find them?"
.IX Subsection "26.2. I have downloaded a Vim plugin or a syntax file or a indent file, or a color scheme or a filetype plugin from the web. Where should I copy these files so that Vim will find them?"
You can place the Vim runtime files (plugins, syntax files, indent files,
color schemes, filetype plugins, etc) under one of the directories
specified in the 'runtimepath' option. To determine the current value of
the 'runtimepath' option, use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set runtimepath
.Ve
.PP
For Unix systems, this is usually the \*(L"$HOME/.vim\*(R" directory. For MS-Windows
systems, this is usually the \f(CW$VIM\fR\evimfiles or \f(CW$HOME\fR\evimfiles directory.
Depending on the type of the runtime file, you have to place it under a
specific directory under the above runtime directory. The names of the
directories are listed below:
.PP
.Vb 10
\& colors/   \- color scheme files
\& compiler/ \- compiler files
\& doc/      \- documentation
\& ftplugin/ \- filetype plugins
\& indent/   \- indent scripts
\& keymap/   \- key mapping files
\& lang/     \- menu translations
\& plugin/   \- plugin scripts
\& syntax/   \- syntax files
\& tutor/    \- files for vimtutor
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help your-runtime-dir\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'runtimepath'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :runtime\fR
.SS "26.3. How do I extend an existing filetype plugin?"
.IX Subsection "26.3. How do I extend an existing filetype plugin?"
You can extend an existing filetype plugin by creating a file in the
after/ directory in any of the 'runtimepath' directories.
.PP
\&\- for small changes to be done after (and in addition to) what is
  already done by the ftplugin installed with Vim, use an after-directory,
  as follows (replacing foobar by the 'filetype' of the concerned
  files):
.PP
.Vb 7
\& \- For changes private to one user:
\&     \- on Windows:
\&         $HOME/vimfiles/after/ftplugin/foobar.vim
\&     \- on Unix\-like OSes:
\&         $HOME/.vim/after/ftplugin/foobar.vim
\& \- For changes affecting all users on the system:
\&     $VIM/vimfiles/after/ftplugin/foobar.vim
.Ve
.PP
\&\- when replacing the whole filetype-plugin by a different version, or
  when installing a new ftplugin for some filetype not yet supported by
  Vim out of the box: use the same paths without the after/ in them. In
  that case you should place near the start of your plugin an \*(L"if...
  finish... endif... let\*(R" block like the one in the plugins distributed
  with Vim.
.PP
All the above paths are given in Vim terminology (which is similar to
Unix terminology, but is understood even by Vim for Windows); they don't
exist by default, so the first time you need them you will have to
create them using mkdir (on any \s-1OS\s0 including DOS/Windows) or md (on
DOS/Windows only). \f(CW$VIM\fR and, on DOS/Windows, \f(CW$HOME\fR, do not necessarily
exist outside Vim. If \f(CW$HOME\fR has no value (or no valid value) inside Vim,
you can use \f(CW$VIM\fR instead; but on any but possibly very old versions of
Windows, \f(CW$HOMEDRIVE\fR and \f(CW$HOMEPATH\fR are defined by the system, and if
\&\f(CW$HOME\fR is undefined at Vim startup, Vim will set it by expanding
\&\f(CW$HOMEDRIVE\fR$HOMEPATH before sourcing your vimrc. To know which values Vim
uses, you can type (in a running Vim):
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :echo $VIM
\& :echo $HOME
.Ve
.PP
If you placed the file in the after/ftplugin runtime directory, then Vim
will first source the existing filetype plugin file and then will source
the new file.  If you placed the file in the \f(CW$VIMRTUNTIME\fR/ftplugin runtime
directory, then Vim will first source the new file and then will source the
existing filetype plugin file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help ftplugin-overrule\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help filetype-plugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help add-filetype-plugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'runtimepath'\fR
.SS "26.4. How do I turn off loading the Vim plugins?"
.IX Subsection "26.4. How do I turn off loading the Vim plugins?"
You can reset the 'loadplugins' option to turn off loading the plugins:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set noloadplugins
.Ve
.PP
You can also specify the \*(L"\-\-noplugin\*(R" command line argument to stop loading
the plugins:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-\-noplugin
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'loadplugins'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-\-noplugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help load-plugins\fR
.SS "26.5. How do I turn on/off loading the filetype plugins?"
.IX Subsection "26.5. How do I turn on/off loading the filetype plugins?"
By default, Vim will not load the filetype plugins. You can configure Vim
to load filetype plugins using the command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& filetype plugin on
.Ve
.PP
You can turn off loading the filetype plugins using:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& filetype plugin off
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :filetype\-plugin\-on\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :filetype\-plugin\-off\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :filetype\fR
.SS "26.6. How do I override settings made in a file type plugin in the global ftplugin directory for all the file types?"
.IX Subsection "26.6. How do I override settings made in a file type plugin in the global ftplugin directory for all the file types?"
You can use an autocommand triggered on the FileType event:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& au Filetype * set formatoptions=xyz
.Ve
.PP
This should at least be after \*(L"filetype on\*(R" in your vimrc. Best is to put
it in your \*(L"myfiletypefile\*(R" file, so that it's always last.
.PP
If you want to override a setting for a particular filetype, then create a
file with the same name as the original filetype plugin in the
~/.vim/after/ftplugin directory For example, to override a setting in the
c.vim filetype plugin, create a c.vim file in the ~/.vim/after/ftplugin
directory and add your preferences in this file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help ftplugin-overrule\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help ftplugins\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help myfiletypefile\fR
.SS "26.7. How do I disable the Vim directory browser plugin?"
.IX Subsection "26.7. How do I disable the Vim directory browser plugin?"
To disable the directory browsing Vim plugin, add the following line to
your .vimrc file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& let g:loaded_netrw = 1
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help netrw\fR
.SS "26.8. How do I set the filetype option for files with names matching a particular pattern or depending on the file extension?"
.IX Subsection "26.8. How do I set the filetype option for files with names matching a particular pattern or depending on the file extension?"
You can set the 'filetype' option for files with names matching a
particular pattern using an autocmd. For example, to set the 'filetype'
option to 'c' for all files with extension '.x', you can use the following
autocmd:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& autocmd! BufRead,BufNewFile *.x     setfiletype c
.Ve
.PP
A better alternative to the above approach is to create a filetype.vim file
in the ~/.vim directory (or in one of the directories specified in the
\&'runtimepath' option) and add the following lines:
.PP
.Vb 7
\& " my filetype file
\& if exists("did_load_filetypes")
\&     finish
\& endif
\& augroup filetypedetect
\&     au! BufRead,BufNewFile *.x       setfiletype c
\& augroup END
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help new-filetype\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 43.2\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :setfiletype\fR
