\&\fB:help 'smartindent'\fR
.SS "27.3. How do I turn off the automatic indentation feature?"
.IX Subsection "27.3. How do I turn off the automatic indentation feature?"
By default, the automatic indentation is not turned on. You must have
configured Vim to do automatic indentation in either .vimrc or .gvimrc
files. You can disable automatic indentation using either,
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :filetype indent off
.Ve
.PP
or
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set nocindent
.Ve
.PP
Also, check the setting for the following options:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :set autoindent?
\& :set smartindent?
\& :set indentexpr?
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cindent'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :filetype\-indent\-off\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'autoindent'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'smartindent'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'indentexpr'\fR
.SS "27.4. How do I change the number of space characters used for the automatic indentation?"
.IX Subsection "27.4. How do I change the number of space characters used for the automatic indentation?"
You can modify the 'shiftwidth' option to change the number of space
characters used for the automatic indentation:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set shiftwidth=4
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'shiftwidth'\fR
.SS "27.5. I am editing a C program using Vim. How do I display the definition of a macro or a variable?"
.IX Subsection "27.5. I am editing a C program using Vim. How do I display the definition of a macro or a variable?"
You can use the \*(L"[d\*(R" command to display the definition of a macro, \*(L"[i\*(R"
command to display the definition of a variable, \*(L"gd\*(R" to goto the local
declaration of a variable and \*(L"gD\*(R" to go to the global Declaration.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help [d\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help [i\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gd\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gD\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help include-search\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 29.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 29.5\fR
.SS "27.6. I am editing a C program using Vim. How do I jump to the beginning or end of a code block from within the block?"
.IX Subsection "27.6. I am editing a C program using Vim. How do I jump to the beginning or end of a code block from within the block?"
You can use '[{' command to jump to the beginning of the code block and ']}
to jump to the end of the code block from inside the block.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help [{\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help ]}\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help various-motions\fR
.SS "27.7. When editing \*(C+ files and when inserting new lines above or below a comment (//) line, Vim automatically inserts the \*(C+ comment character (//) at the beginning of the line. How do I disable this?"
.IX Subsection "27.7. When editing files and when inserting new lines above or below a comment (//) line, Vim automatically inserts the comment character (//) at the beginning of the line. How do I disable this?"
This automatic insertion of the comment leader (//) when new lines
are added is controlled by three flags in the 'formatoptions'
option:  'c', 'r' and 'o'.  'c' enables auto-wrapping of comment
lines when typing extends beyond the right margin.  'r' enables the
automatic insertion of the comment leader when <Enter> is pressed
while editing a comment line.  'o' enables the automatic insertion
of the comment leader when a new line is opened above or below an
existing comment line by typing O or o in Normal mode.
.PP
You can stop Vim from automatically inserting the comment leader
when typing <Enter> within a comment or when opening a new line by
removing the 'r' and 'o' flags from 'formatoptions'.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&   :set formatoptions\-=r
\&   :set formatoptions\-=o
.Ve
.PP
The default filetype plugin for C and \*(C+ files
($VIMRUNTIME/ftplugin/c.vim) adds the 'r' and 'o' flags to the
\&'formatoptions' option.  If you want to override this for \*(C+ files,
then you can add the above lines to the
~/.vim/after/ftplugin/cpp.vim file.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help formatoptions\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 30.6\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help format-comments\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help filetype-plugins\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help ftplugin-overrule\fR
.SS "27.8. How do I add the comment character '#' to a set of lines at the beginning of each line?"
.IX Subsection "27.8. How do I add the comment character '#' to a set of lines at the beginning of each line?"
First, select the first character in all the lines using visual block mode
(CTRL-V). Press 'I' to start inserting characters at the beginning of the
line. Enter the comment character and then stop the insert mode by pressing
<Esc>. Vim will automatically insert the entered characters at the
beginning of all the selected lines.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help visual-block\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help blockwise-operators\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help v_b_I\fR
.SS "27.9. How do I edit a header file with the same name as the corresponding C source file?"
.IX Subsection "27.9. How do I edit a header file with the same name as the corresponding C source file?"
You can use the following command to edit a header file with the same name
as the corresponding C source file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :e %:t:r.h
.Ve
.PP
You can use the following command to edit the file in a new split window:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :sp %:t:r.h
.Ve
.PP
In the above commands, the percent sign expands to the name of the current
file.  The \*(L":t\*(R" modifier extracts the tail (last component) of the
filename. The \*(L":r\*(R" modifier extracts the root of the filename.  The .h is
appended to the resulting name to get the header filename.
.PP
Another approach is to use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :sfind %:t:r.h
.Ve
.PP
This command will search for the header file in the directories specified
in the 'path' option.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help cmdline-special\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help filename-modifiers\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :sfind\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'path'\fR
.SS "27.10. How do I automatically insert comment leaders while typing comments?"
.IX Subsection "27.10. How do I automatically insert comment leaders while typing comments?"
To automatically insert comment leaders while typing comments, add the 'r'
and 'o' flags to the 'formatoptions' option.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set formatoptions+=ro
.Ve
.PP
You may also want to add the 'c' flag to auto-wrap comments using the
\&'textwidth' option setting and the 'q' flag to format comments with the
\&\*(L"gq\*(R" command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set formatoptions=croq
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 30.6\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help format-comments\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'comments'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help fo-table\fR
.SH "QUICKFIX"
.IX Header "QUICKFIX"
.SS "28.1. How do I build programs from Vim?"
.IX Subsection "28.1. How do I build programs from Vim?"
You can use the \*(L":make\*(R" command to build programs from Vim. The \*(L":make\*(R"
command runs the program specified by the 'makeprg' option.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 30.1\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :make_makeprg\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'makeprg'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'makeef'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :make\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quickfix\fR
.SS "28.2. When I run the make command in Vim I get the errors listed as the compiler compiles the program. When it finishes this list disappears and I have to use the  :clist command to see the error message again. Is there any other way to see these error messages?"
.IX Subsection "28.2. When I run the make command in Vim I get the errors listed as the compiler compiles the program. When it finishes this list disappears and I have to use the :clist command to see the error message again. Is there any other way to see these error messages?"
You can use the \*(L":copen\*(R" or \*(L":cwindow\*(R" command to open the quickfix window
that contains the compiler output. You can select different error lines
from this window and jump to the corresponding line in the source code.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :copen\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :cwindow\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help quickfix\fR
.SS "28.3. How can I perform a command for each item in the quickfix/location list?"
.IX Subsection "28.3. How can I perform a command for each item in the quickfix/location list?"
Starting from Vim 7.4.858 Vim provides the new commands :cfdo, :cdo,
:lfdo and :ldo. They work by iterating over all items in the quickfix
list and performing a command on each. The difference is, that the :lfdo
and :ldo commands iterate over the location list entries, while the
:cfdo and :cdo commands operate on the items in the quickfix list. Also,
the :cfdo and :lfdo operate on all different files, while the :cdo and
:ldo commands operate on each item in the quickfix/location list.
.PP
For example you could vimgrep all C files in the current directory for a
search string \*(L"Foobar\*(R":
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :vimgrep /Foobar/ *.c
.Ve
.PP
and as this populates your quickfix list, you could simply replace all
occurences by using:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :cdo :%s/Foobar/Foobaz | upd
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :cfdo\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :cdo\fR
.SH "FOLDING"
.IX Header "FOLDING"
.SS "29.1. How do I extend the Vim folding support?"
.IX Subsection "29.1. How do I extend the Vim folding support?"
You can use the 'foldexpr' option to fold using a user specified function.
For example, to fold subroutines of the following form into a single line:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& sub foo {
\&   my $barf;
\&   $barf = 3;
\&   return $barf;
\& }
.Ve
.PP
You can use the following commands:
.PP
.Vb 12
\& set foldmethod=expr
\& set foldexpr=MyFoldExpr(v:lnum)
\& fun! MyFoldExpr(line)
\&     let str = getline(a:line)
\&     if str =~ \*(Aq^sub\e>\*(Aq
\&         return \*(Aq1\*(Aq
\&     elseif str =~ \*(Aq^}\*(Aq
\&         return \*(Aq<1\*(Aq
\&     else
\&         return foldlevel(a:line \- 1)
\&     endif
\& endfun
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldexpr'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help fold-expr\fR
.SS "29.2. When I enable folding by setting the 'foldmethod' option, all the folds are closed. How do I prevent this?"
.IX Subsection "29.2. When I enable folding by setting the 'foldmethod' option, all the folds are closed. How do I prevent this?"
You can set the 'foldlevelstart' option to a particular value to close only
folds above the specified value.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set foldlevelstart=99
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldlevelstart'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldlevel'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help fold-foldlevel\fR
.SS "29.3. How do I control how many folds will be opened when I start editing a file?"
.IX Subsection "29.3. How do I control how many folds will be opened when I start editing a file?"
You can modify the 'foldlevelstart' option to control the number of folds
that will be opened when you start editing a file. To start editing with
all the folds closed:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set foldlevelstart=0
.Ve
.PP
To start editing with all the folds opened, you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set foldlevelstart=999
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldlevelstart'\fR
.SS "29.4. How do I open and close folds using the mouse?"
.IX Subsection "29.4. How do I open and close folds using the mouse?"
You can click on the + and \- characters displayed at the leftmost column to
open and close fold. For this to work, you have to set the 'foldcolumn'
to a value greater than zero:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set foldcolumn=2
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldcolumn'\fR
.SS "29.5. How do I change the text displayed for a closed fold?"
.IX Subsection "29.5. How do I change the text displayed for a closed fold?"
You can use the 'foldtext' option to change the text displayed for a closed
fold.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'foldtext'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help fold-foldtext\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fillchars'\fR
.SS "29.6. How do I store and restore manually created folds across different Vim invocations?"
.IX Subsection "29.6. How do I store and restore manually created folds across different Vim invocations?"
You can use the \*(L":mkview\*(R" command to store manually created folds. Later,
you can use the \*(L":loadview\*(R" command to restore the folds. For this to work,
the 'viewoptions' must contain \*(L"folds\*(R".
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 28.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mkview\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :loadview\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viewoptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'viewdir'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :mksession\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'sessionoptions'\fR
.SS "29.7. I have enabled syntax based folding. Why is Vim so slow?"
.IX Subsection "29.7. I have enabled syntax based folding. Why is Vim so slow?"
Syntax based folding is currently rather slow in Vim and will possibly
slow down Vim considerably. There is an issue in the todo list to fix
this, but the todo list is rather long and it may take a while until
this will be fixed.
.PP
You can find the issue in the todo list, if you read
.PP
\&\fB:help todo.txt\fR
.PP
followed by a search for \*(L"folding with 'foldmethod'\*(R"
.PP
A workaround is to temporarily set the foldmethod to manual while in
insert mode. This is described in the wiki at:
http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Keep_folds_closed_while_inserting_text
.SH "VIM WITH EXTERNAL APPLICATIONS"
.IX Header "VIM WITH EXTERNAL APPLICATIONS"
.SS "30.1. Can I run a shell inside a Vim window?"
.IX Subsection "30.1. Can I run a shell inside a Vim window?"
Currently Vim doesn't have support for running shell and other external
commands inside a Vim window.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help shell-window\fR
.PP
The Neovim project however has added the \*(L":terminal\*(R" command which opens
a new shell prompt. To read more about Neovim, look at their webpage
http://neovim.io
.PP
Alternatively, you can try using the Unix \*(L"screen\*(R", \*(L"tmux\*(R" or \*(L"splitvt\*(R"
utility.
.PP
Following is a post from the vim_use mailinglist
(http://groups.google.com/group/vim_use/msg/22c97ebfd6a978eb)
.PP
\&\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
Date: Mon, 24 May 2010
Subject: Re: Terminal into vim, best options???
From: Nico Raffo
To: vim_use
.PP
There are quite a few options out there, all with their strengths and
weaknesses. Shell integration is at the top of the Vim wish list. I'm
sure Bram would be more interested in including it if someone
developed and maintained a kick-ass patch :\-)
.PP
Here is a (quite biased) overview of what's currently available:
.PP
Conque Shell
\&\s-1URL:\s0 http://code.google.com/p/conque/
Author: Nico Raffo (me!)
Requirements: *nix, python-enabled vim
Type: Plugin
.PP
Conque is a Vim plugin, written with Vim script and python. It turns
your Vim buffer into a terminal emulator. In \s-1INSERT\s0 mode your buffer
behaves like a standard unix terminal. In \s-1NORMAL\s0 mode you can navigate/
search/page through the terminal output.
.PP
Pros:
 * Relatively easy to install
 * Near complete \s-1VT100\s0 support (you can run emacs in a vim buffer)
 * Use of Vim features in terminal, including syntax highlighting,
   copy/paste, etc
 * Active development
.PP
Cons:
 * No Windows support (coming with Vim 7.3)
 * Can be slow, especially with programs which use a lot of terminal
   colors
.PP
Vimshell
\&\s-1URL:\s0 http://github.com/Shougo/vimshell + http://github.com/Shougo/vimproc
Author: Shougo M
Requirements: Works on both *nix and Windows. One small, independent
component may need to be compiled from C source.
Type: Plugin
.PP
Vimshell is a shell, written in the Vim scripting language, that runs
in a Vim buffer. The shell was written to take full advantage of all
of Vim's features, for example you can use Vim's omnicomplete
features, or any other normal mode Vim commands, to edit your command
line. Great potential, but missing a few features, particularly
regarding interactive programs.
.PP
Pros:
 * Relatively easy to install
 * Edit the command line with Vim, full use of Vim features in both
   normal and insert mode
 * Very fast, since there is no background process required
 * Windows support
 * Active development
.PP
Cons:
 * Very limited support of interactive programs such as bash, mysql or
   python.
 * Shell has incomplete functionality compared to bash, etc.
 * Documentation only available in Japanese.
.PP
screen.vim (Vim + screen/tmux)
\&\s-1URL:\s0 http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=2711
Author: Eric Van Dewoestine
Requirements: *nix
Type: Plugin
.PP
screen.vim is a Vim plugin which streamlines and enhances the
experience of running split screen terminal with Vim running in one of
the windows and a terminal running in the other. It uses the programs
screen or tmux to manage the split windows and to run the terminal
emulation. Both of these programs are very mature, and will give a
better terminal experience than any other option. However since the
terminal is running independently of Vim, you won't be able to use Vim
commands to interact with the terminal output.
.PP
Pros:
 * Easy to install
 * Great shell support
 * Active development
.PP
Cons:
 * No use of Vim commands to manage the shell window
 * Relatively little integration between Vim and the shell
.PP
Vim-Shell
\&\s-1URL:\s0 http://www.wana.at/vimshell/
Author: Thomas Wanda
Requirements: *nix, patch and recompile Vim from source
Type: Extension
.PP
Vim-Shell is a Vim extension which converts a buffer into a terminal
emulator. The shell window itself is very fast and functionality is
very strong. It is works great for running complex interactive
programs. However the Vim buffer where it runs is no longer editable
(you can't scroll up, or even move the cursor). The last official
release was for Vim 7.0, although time spent searching on Google will
turn up patches for Vim 7.1 and 7.2.
.PP
Pros:
 * Near complete \s-1VT100\s0 support (you can run emacs in a vim buffer, and
   just about anything else)
 * Very fast. Compiled into the C source
.PP
Cons:
 * Relatively difficult to install
 * No use of Vim features to navigate terminal output
 * No Windows or Mac support.
 * No development activity since 2006
.PP
Vimsh
\&\s-1URL:\s0 http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=165
Author: Brian Sturk
Requirements: python-enabled vim
Type: Plugin
.PP
Vimsh is a Vim plugin which allows you to run interactive programs in
a vim buffer. It provides a nice option for Windows use, but
functionality is overall less mature than the other options.
.PP
Pros:
 * Relatively easy to install
 * Use Vim commands to edit commands and navigate terminal output
 * Support in both *nix and Windows (no interactive programs in
   Windows)
.PP
Cons:
 * Limited functionality
 * Inactive development
.PP
