.SS "30.2. How do I pass the word under the cursor to an external command?"
.IX Subsection "30.2. How do I pass the word under the cursor to an external command?"
You can use the special keyword <cword> to pass the word under the cursor
to an external command. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :!dict <cword>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :<cword\fR>
.SS "30.3. How do I get the output of a shell command into a Vim buffer?"
.IX Subsection "30.3. How do I get the output of a shell command into a Vim buffer?"
You can use the \*(L":r !\*(R" command to get the output of a shell command into a
Vim buffer. For example, to insert the output of the \*(L"ls\*(R" shell command,
you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :r !ls
.Ve
.PP
To insert the output of the shell command above the first line use the
following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :0r !ls
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :r!\fR
.SS "30.4. How do I pipe the contents of the current buffer to an external command and replace the contents of the buffer with the output from the command?"
.IX Subsection "30.4. How do I pipe the contents of the current buffer to an external command and replace the contents of the buffer with the output from the command?"
You can use the :! command to pipe the contents of the current buffer to an
external command and replace the contents of the buffer with the output
from the command. For example, to sort the contents of the current buffer,
using the Unix sort command, you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :%!sort
.Ve
.PP
To sort only lines 10\-20, you can use the following command
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :10,20!sort
.Ve
.PP
Also, if you want to pipe a buffer to an external command but not put the
results back in the buffer, you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :w !sort
.Ve
.PP
The above command will pipe the entire buffer to the sort command.  Note,
that the space between the 'w' and the '!' is critical.  To pipe only a
range of lines, you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :10,20w !sort
.Ve
.PP
The above command will pipe the lines 10\-20 to the sort command.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :range!\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.9\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :w_c\fR
.SS "30.5. How do I sort a section of my file?"
.IX Subsection "30.5. How do I sort a section of my file?"
You use the \*(L":sort\*(R" command like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   :5,100sort
.Ve
.PP
Using the \*(L":sort\*(R" command provides many options, you can sort numerical on
the first found decimal number using:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   :%sort n
.Ve
.PP
Or you can specify to sort on the text, starting at virtual column 8:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   :%sort /.*\e%8v/
.Ve
.PP
Alternatively can pipe a section of the file to the Unix \*(L"sort\*(R" utility to
sort the file. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :5,100!sort
.Ve
.PP
You can also use a visual block, and use the \*(L"!sort\*(R" command on the
selected block.
.PP
See also:
\&\fB:help :sort\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help filter\fR
.SS "30.6. How do I use Vim as a pager?"
.IX Subsection "30.6. How do I use Vim as a pager?"
You can use Vim as a pager using the \f(CW$VIMRUNTIME\fR/macros/less.sh shell
script, supplied as part of the standard Vim distribution. This shell
script uses the \f(CW$VIMRUNTIME\fR/macros/less.vim Vim script to provide less like
key bindings.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help less\fR
.SS "30.7. How do I view Unix man pages from inside Vim?"
.IX Subsection "30.7. How do I view Unix man pages from inside Vim?"
You can view Unix man pages, inside Vim, using the man.vim plugin supplied
as part of the standard Vim distribution. To use this plugin, add the
following line to your startup vimrc file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& runtime ftplugin/man.vim
.Ve
.PP
You can also press the K key to run the program specified by the
\&'keywordprg' option with the keyword under the cursor. By default,
\&'keywordprg' is set to run man on the keyword under the cursor.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help ft-man-plugin\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help K\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'keywordprg'\fR
.SS "30.8. How do I change the diff command used by the Vim diff support?"
.IX Subsection "30.8. How do I change the diff command used by the Vim diff support?"
By default, the Vim diff support uses the 'diff' command. You can change
this by changing the 'diffexpr' option.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help diff-diffexpr\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'diffexpr'\fR
.SS "30.9. How do I use the Vim diff mode without folding?"
.IX Subsection "30.9. How do I use the Vim diff mode without folding?"
You can use the following command-line to start Vim with two filenames
and use the diff mode without folding:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-o file1 file2 "+windo set diff scrollbind scrollopt+=hor nowrap"
.Ve
.PP
If you like vertically split windows, then replace \*(L"\-o\*(R" with \*(L"\-O\*(R".
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help vimdiff\fR
.SH "GUI VIM"
.IX Header "GUI VIM"
.SS "31.1. How do I create buffer specific menus?"
.IX Subsection "31.1. How do I create buffer specific menus?"
Adding support for buffer specific menus is in the Vim \s-1TODO\s0 list. In the
mean time, you can try Michael Geddes's plugin, buffermenu.vim:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& http://vim.sourceforge.net/scripts/script.php?script_id=246
.Ve
.SS "31.2. How do I change the font used by \s-1GUI\s0 Vim?"
.IX Subsection "31.2. How do I change the font used by GUI Vim?"
You can change the 'guifont' option to change the font used by \s-1GUI\s0 Vim.  To
display the current value of this option, you can use
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guifont?
.Ve
.PP
You can add the displayed font name to the .vimrc file to use the font
across Vim sessions. For example, add the following line to the .vimrc file
to use Andale Mono font.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& set guifont=Andale_Mono:h10:cANSI
.Ve
.PP
For Win32, \s-1GTK\s0 and Photon version of Vim, you can use the following command
to bringup a dialog which will help you in changing the guifont:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guifont=*
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \-font Vim command line option to specify the font used
for normal text.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guifont'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guifontset'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guifontwide'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help font-sizes\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-font\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-boldfont\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-italicfont\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-menufont\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-menufontset\fR
.SS "31.3. When starting \s-1GUI\s0 Vim, how do I specify the location of the \s-1GVIM \s0 window?"
.IX Subsection "31.3. When starting GUI Vim, how do I specify the location of the GVIM window?"
You can use the \*(L"\-geometry\*(R" command line argument to specify the location
of the \s-1GUI\s0 Vim window. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ gvim \-geometry 80x25+100+300
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 31.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-geom\fR
.SS "31.4. How do I add a horizontal scrollbar in GVim?"
.IX Subsection "31.4. How do I add a horizontal scrollbar in GVim?"
You can enable the horizontal scrollbar by modifying the 'guioptions'
option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guioptions+=b
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guioptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-horiz-scroll\fR
.SS "31.5. How do I make the scrollbar appear in the left side by default?"
.IX Subsection "31.5. How do I make the scrollbar appear in the left side by default?"
You can add the 'l' flag to the 'guioptions' option to make the scrollbar
appear in the left side.
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set guioptions+=l
\& :set guioptions\-=r
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guioptions'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-scrollbars\fR
.SS "31.6. How do I remove the Vim menubar?"
.IX Subsection "31.6. How do I remove the Vim menubar?"
You can remove the Vim menubar by removing the 'm' flag from the
\&'guioptions' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guioptions\-=m
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guioptions'\fR
.SS "31.7. I am using \s-1GUI\s0 Vim. When I press the \s-1ALT\s0 key and a letter, the menu starting with that letter is selected. I don't want this behavior as I want to map the ALT\-<key> combination. How do I do this?"
.IX Subsection "31.7. I am using GUI Vim. When I press the ALT key and a letter, the menu starting with that letter is selected. I don't want this behavior as I want to map the ALT-<key> combination. How do I do this?"
You can use the 'winaltkeys' option to disable the use of the \s-1ALT\s0 key to
select a menu item:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set winaltkeys=no
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'winaltkeys'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :simalt\fR
.SS "31.8. Is it possible to scroll the text by dragging the scrollbar so that the cursor stays in the original location?"
.IX Subsection "31.8. Is it possible to scroll the text by dragging the scrollbar so that the cursor stays in the original location?"
The way Vim is designed, the cursor position has to be in a visible spot in
normal, visual, select and insert mode. This cannot be changed without
modifying Vim. When the scrollbar is used, the cursor will be moved so that
it is always visible. Another approach to solving this problem is to use
the Vim marks. You can mark the current cursor position using ma. Then
scroll to a different part of the text and jump back to the old position
using `a. You can also try the following suggestion from the Vim Online
website:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/VimTip320
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help mark-motions\fR
.ie n .SS "31.9. How do I get gvim to start browsing files in a particular directory when using the "":browse"" command?"
.el .SS "31.9. How do I get gvim to start browsing files in a particular directory when using the ``:browse'' command?"
.IX Subsection "31.9. How do I get gvim to start browsing files in a particular directory when using the :browse command?"
You can set the 'browsedir' option to the default directory to use for the
\&\*(L":browse\*(R" command.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set browsedir=\*(Aq<your_dir>\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'browsedir'\fR
.SS "31.10. For some questions, like when a file is changed outside of Vim, Vim displays a \s-1GUI\s0 dialog box. How do I replace this \s-1GUI\s0 dialog box with a console dialog box?"
.IX Subsection "31.10. For some questions, like when a file is changed outside of Vim, Vim displays a GUI dialog box. How do I replace this GUI dialog box with a console dialog box?"
You can set the 'c' flag in the 'guioptions' option to configure Vim to use
console dialogs instead of \s-1GUI\s0 dialogs:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guioptions+=c
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guioptions'\fR
.SS "31.11. I am trying to use \s-1GUI\s0 Vim as the editor for my xxx application. When the xxx application launches \s-1GUI\s0 Vim to edit a file, the control immediately returns to the xxx application. How do I start \s-1GUI\s0 Vim, so that the control returns to the xxx application only after I quit Vim?"
.IX Subsection "31.11. I am trying to use GUI Vim as the editor for my xxx application. When the xxx application launches GUI Vim to edit a file, the control immediately returns to the xxx application. How do I start GUI Vim, so that the control returns to the xxx application only after I quit Vim?"
You have to start \s-1GUI\s0 Vim with the '\-f' (foreground) command line option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ gvim \-f
.Ve
.PP
By default, \s-1GUI\s0 Vim will disconnect from the program that started Vim. With
the '\-f' option, \s-1GUI\s0 Vim will not disconnect from the program that started
it.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-fork\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-f\fR
.ie n .SS "31.12. Why does the ""Select Font"" dialog doesn't show all the fonts installed in my system?"
.el .SS "31.12. Why does the ``Select Font'' dialog doesn't show all the fonts installed in my system?"
.IX Subsection "31.12. Why does the Select Font dialog doesn't show all the fonts installed in my system?"
Vim supports only fixed width (mono-spaced) fonts. Proportional fonts are
not supported.  In the \*(L"Select Font\*(R" dialog, only fixed width fonts will be
displayed.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help font-sizes\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guifont'\fR
.SS "31.13. How do I use the mouse in Vim command-line mode?"
.IX Subsection "31.13. How do I use the mouse in Vim command-line mode?"
You can set the 'c' flag in the 'mouse' option to use mouse in the Vim
command-line mode:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set mouse+=c
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help mouse-using\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-mouse\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 09.2\fR
.SS "31.14. When I use the middle mouse button to scroll text, it pastes the last copied text. How do I disable this behavior?"
.IX Subsection "31.14. When I use the middle mouse button to scroll text, it pastes the last copied text. How do I disable this behavior?"
You can map the middle mouse button to <Nop> to disable the middle mouse
button:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :map  <MiddleMouse> <Nop>
\& :map! <MiddleMouse> <Nop>
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-mouse-mapping\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help <Nop\fR>
.SS "31.15. How do I change the location and size of a \s-1GUI\s0 Vim window?"
.IX Subsection "31.15. How do I change the location and size of a GUI Vim window?"
You can use the \*(L"winpos\*(R" command to change the Vim window position. To
change the size of the window, you can modify the \*(L"lines\*(R" and \*(L"columns\*(R"
options.
.PP
For example, the following commands will position the \s-1GUI\s0 Vim window at the
X,Y co-ordinates 50,50 and set the number of lines to 50 and the number of
columns to 80.
.PP
.Vb 3
\& :winpos 50 50
\& :set lines=50
\& :set columns=80
.Ve
.PP
The arguments to the 'winpos' command specify the pixel co-ordinates of the
Vim window. The 'lines' and 'columns' options specify the number of lines
and characters to use for the height and the width of the window
respectively.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 31.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :winpos\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'lines'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'columns'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help GUIEnter\fR
.SS "31.16. When splitting the Vim window vertically, Vim changes the position."
.IX Subsection "31.16. When splitting the Vim window vertically, Vim changes the position."
This is a known problem. When you are splitting the Vim window, Vim will
try to draw a scrollbar. Since this changes the gui window, Vim tries to
resize its main window to keep the same position and this will cause Vim
to move its position. This happens on Windows with a multi-window setup or
a window that was \*(L"snapped\*(R" to a certain position.
.PP
A workaournd to this problem is, to remove gui scrollbars, e.g.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guioptions\-=L
.Ve
.SH "VIM ON UNIX"
.IX Header "VIM ON UNIX"
.SS "32.1. I am running Vim in a xterm. When I press the CTRL-S key, Vim freezes. What should I do now?"
.IX Subsection "32.1. I am running Vim in a xterm. When I press the CTRL-S key, Vim freezes. What should I do now?"
Many terminal emulators and real terminal drivers use the CTRL-S key to
stop the data from arriving so that you can stop a fast scrolling display
to look at it (also allowed older terminals to slow down the computer so
that it did not get buffer overflows).  You can start the output again by
pressing the CTRL-Q key.
.PP
When you press the CTRL-S key, the terminal driver will stop sending the
output data. As a result of this, it will look like Vim is hung. If you
press the CTRL-Q key, then everything will be back to normal.
.PP
You can turn off the terminal driver flow control using the 'stty' command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ stty \-ixon \-ixoff
.Ve
.PP
or, you can change the keys used for the terminal flow control, using the
following commands:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& $ stty stop <char>
\& $ stty start <char>
.Ve
.SS "32.2. I am seeing weird screen update problems in Vim. What can I do to solve this screen/display update problems?"
.IX Subsection "32.2. I am seeing weird screen update problems in Vim. What can I do to solve this screen/display update problems?"
You have to use a proper terminal emulator like xterm with correct \s-1TERM\s0
settings (TERM=xterm) and a correct terminfo/termcap file.
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'term'\fR
.SS "32.3. I am using the terminal/console version of Vim. In insertmode, When I press the backspace key, the character before the cursor is not erased. How do I configure Vim to do this?"
.IX Subsection "32.3. I am using the terminal/console version of Vim. In insertmode, When I press the backspace key, the character before the cursor is not erased. How do I configure Vim to do this?"
You have to make sure that Vim gets the correct keycode for the backpspace
key. You can try using the command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :fixdel
.Ve
.PP
Make sure the \s-1TERM\s0 environment variable is set to the correct terminal
name. You can try using the 'stty' command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ stty erase ^H
.Ve
.PP
where, you have to enter the ^H character by pressing the CTRL-V key and
then the CTRL-H key. Also check the value of your 'backspace' setting.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :fixdel\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help Linux-backspace\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help NetBSD-backspace\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'backspace'\fR
.SS "32.4. I am using Vim in a xterm. When I quit Vim, the screen contents are restored back to the original contents. How do I disable this?"
.IX Subsection "32.4. I am using Vim in a xterm. When I quit Vim, the screen contents are restored back to the original contents. How do I disable this?"
The xterm has a capability called \*(L"alternate screen\*(R".  If this capability
is present, vim switches to that alternate screen upon startup and back on
exit, thus restoring the original screen contents.  To disable this
feature, add the following line to your .vimrc file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set t_ti= t_te=
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'restorescreen'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help xterm-screens\fR
.SS "32.5. When I start Vim, it takes quite a few seconds to start. How do I minimize the startup time?"
.IX Subsection "32.5. When I start Vim, it takes quite a few seconds to start. How do I minimize the startup time?"
This may be related to Vim opening the X display for setting the xterm
title and using the X clipboard. Make sure the \s-1DISPLAY\s0 variable is set to
point to the correct host. Try using the command line:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-X
.Ve
.PP
This will prevent Vim from opening the X display. With this command-line
option, the X clipboard cannot be used and also Vim will not be able to
change the xterm title.
.PP
You can also set the 'clipboard' option to
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set clipboard=exclude:.*
.Ve
.PP
This has the same effect as using the \-X command-line argument.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \-X\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'clipboard'\fR
.PP
If the clipboard is not the cause of the slow startup, it might be a
plugin that slows down Vim. In that case, you can use the \-\-startuptime
argument to debug this further. You can do:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-\-startuptime vim_startup.log
.Ve
.PP
and the timing will be written to the file vim_startup.log. For even
more advanced profiling, you can use the profiling feature, that is
available in huge builds of Vim. To do so, call Vim like this:
.PP
.Vb 6
\& $ vim \-\-cmd \*(Aqprofile start profile.log\*(Aq \e
\&   \-\-cmd \*(Aqprofile func *\*(Aq \e
\&   \-\-cmd \*(Aqprofile file *\*(Aq \e
\&   \-c \*(Aqprofdel func *\*(Aq \e
\&   \-c \*(Aqprofdel file *\*(Aq \e
\&   \-c \*(Aqqa!\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
After running this, you will have a file profile.log in your current
directory. To further analyse this, open the file profile.log and run:
.PP
.Vb 5
\& " Open profile.log file in vim first
\& :let timings=[]
\& :g/^SCRIPT/call add(timings, [getline(\*(Aq.\*(Aq)[len(\*(AqSCRIPT  \*(Aq):], matchstr(getline(line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq)+1), \*(Aq^Sourced \ezs\ed\e+\*(Aq)]+map(getline(line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq)+2, line(\*(Aq.\*(Aq)+3), \*(Aqmatchstr(v:val, \*(Aq\*(Aq\ed\e+\e.\ed\e+$\*(Aq\*(Aq)\*(Aq))
\& :enew
\& :call setline(\*(Aq.\*(Aq, [\*(Aqcount total (s)   self (s)  script\*(Aq]+map(copy(timings), \*(Aqprintf("%5u %9s   %8s  %s", v:val[1], v:val[2], v:val[3], v:val[0])\*(Aq))
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \-\-startuptime\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help profiling\fR
.SS "32.6. How can I make the cursor in gvim in unix stop blinking?"
.IX Subsection "32.6. How can I make the cursor in gvim in unix stop blinking?"
You can modify the 'guicursor' option, to stop the cursor from blinking.
For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set guicursor=a:blinkon0
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'guicursor'\fR
.SS "32.7. How do I change the menu font on \s-1GTK\s0 Vim?"
.IX Subsection "32.7. How do I change the menu font on GTK Vim?"
You can modify the ~/.gtkrc file to change the menu font on \s-1GTK\s0 Vim. For
example:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& style "default"
\& { font ="smooth09" }
\& class "*" style "default"
.Ve
.PP
The last line changes the font of all widgets.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help gui-gtk\fR
.SS "32.8. How do I prevent <Ctrl\-Z> from suspending Vim?"
.IX Subsection "32.8. How do I prevent <Ctrl-Z> from suspending Vim?"
You can map <Ctrl\-Z> to prevent the suspending. Here are some suggestions:
.PP
\&\- Make <Ctrl\-Z> do nothing:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <C\-Z> <Nop>
.Ve
.PP
\&\- Make <Ctrl\-Z> start a shell:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <C\-Z> :shell<CR>
.Ve
.PP
\&\- Make <Ctrl\-Z> give an error message:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :map <C\-Z> :"suspending disabled<CR>
.Ve
.PP
For the last example, the double quote is necessary in order to keep the
message on the status line.
.SS "32.9. When I kill the xterm running Vim, the Vim process continues to run and takes up a lot of \s-1CPU \s0(99%) time. Why is this happening?"
.IX Subsection "32.9. When I kill the xterm running Vim, the Vim process continues to run and takes up a lot of CPU (99%) time. Why is this happening?"
When Vim is built with support for Python interface, you will have this
problem. This is a known problem with the python thread library and Vim.  To
solve this problem, use a Vim binary built without the Python interface.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help +python\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help python\fR
.SS "32.10. How do I get the Vim syntax highlighting to work in a Unix terminal?"
.IX Subsection "32.10. How do I get the Vim syntax highlighting to work in a Unix terminal?"
The easiest and simplest way to get Vim syntax highlighting is to use the
\&\s-1GUI\s0 version of Vim (\s-1GVIM\s0). To get syntax highlighting to work in the
console/terminal version of Vim, you have to run a terminal emulator (like
Xfree86 xterm or rxvt or dtterm) that supports color. Note that if a
terminal emulator supports changing the background and foreground colors,
that does not mean that it also supports \s-1ANSI\s0 escape sequences for changing
the color. You can download the latest version of Xfree86 xterm from
http://dickey.his.com/xterm/xterm.html. You can download the latest version
of rxvt from http://www.rxvt.org. You have to install the terminfo/termcap
file that supports colors for the terminal emulator. Also, set the \s-1TERM\s0
environment variable to the correct name of the term that supports colors.
.PP
You can use the colortest.vim script supplied with the Vim runtime
package to test the color setup. To use this script, follow these steps:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :e $VIMRUNTIME/syntax/colortest.vim
\& :source %
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 06.2\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help terminal-colors\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help termcap-colors\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help startup-terminal\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help xterm-color\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help colortest.vim\fR
.SH "VIM ON MS-WINDOWS"
.IX Header "VIM ON MS-WINDOWS"
.SS "33.1. In MS-Windows, CTRL-V doesn't start the blockwise visual mode. What happened?"
.IX Subsection "33.1. In MS-Windows, CTRL-V doesn't start the blockwise visual mode. What happened?"
The mswin.vim script provides key mappings and options to make Vim behave
like a MS-Windows application. One of the keys mapped is CTRL-V which is
used for pasting text in MS-Windows applications. This will disable the use
of CTRL-V to start the blockwise visual mode. The mswin.vim script maps
CTRL-Q for staring the blockwise visual mode. So you can use CTRL-Q instead
of CTRL-V.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-V\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-V-alternative\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help CTRL-Q\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 10.5\fR
.SS "33.2. When I press the CTRL-Y key, it acts like the CTRL-R key. How do I configure Vim to treat CTRL-Y as CTRL-Y?"
.IX Subsection "33.2. When I press the CTRL-Y key, it acts like the CTRL-R key. How do I configure Vim to treat CTRL-Y as CTRL-Y?"
The mapping of the CTRL-Y key to the CTRL-R key is done by the mswin.vim
script. The mswin.vim script maps CTRL-Y to make Vim behave like a standard
MS-Windows application. This is explained in \*(L":help CTRL-Y\*(R". You can either
comment out the line in mswin.vim that maps the CTRL-Y key or you can
remove the line in your .vimrc file that sources the mswin.vim script.
.SS "33.3. How do I start \s-1GUI\s0 Vim in a maximized window always?"
.IX Subsection "33.3. How do I start GUI Vim in a maximized window always?"
You can use the \*(L"simalt\*(R" command to maximize the Vim window. You can use
the GUIEnter autocmd to maximize the Vim window on startup:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& autocmd GUIEnter * simalt ~x
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :simalt\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help GUIEnter\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help gui\-win32\-maximized\fR
.SS "33.4. After doing some editing operations, Vim freezes. The cursor becomes an empty rectangle. I am not able enter any characters. What is happening?"
.IX Subsection "33.4. After doing some editing operations, Vim freezes. The cursor becomes an empty rectangle. I am not able enter any characters. What is happening?"
Most probably, you used the mouse wheel to scroll the text in Vim. There is
a known problem in using intellimouse mouse wheel with Vim. To avoid this
problem, disable Universal scrolling support for Vim.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help intellimouse-wheel-problems\fR
.SS "33.5. I am using Windows \s-1XP,\s0 the display speed of maximized GVim is very slow. What can I do to speed the display updates?"
.IX Subsection "33.5. I am using Windows XP, the display speed of maximized GVim is very slow. What can I do to speed the display updates?"
This may be due to the fact that you have enabled 'Smooth edges of screen
fonts' in the display properties. Try turning off font smoothing or try
changing the smoothing method to \*(L"Standard\*(R".
.SS "33.6. What are the recommended settings for using Vim with cygwin?"
.IX Subsection "33.6. What are the recommended settings for using Vim with cygwin?"
You may want to set the following shell related Vim settings:
.PP
.Vb 7
\& :set shellcmdflag=\-c
\& :set shellquote=
\& :set shellslash          " Use the forward slash for expansion.
\& :set shellxquote=\e"
\& :set shell=d:\ecygwin\ebin\ebash.exe " Use the bash shell
\& :set shellpipe=2>&1| tee
\& :set shellredir=>%s 2>&1
.Ve
.SS "33.7. I am trying to use \s-1GNU\s0 diff with Vim diff mode. When I run the diff from command line, it works. When I try to use the diff with Vim it doesn't work. What should I do now?"
.IX Subsection "33.7. I am trying to use GNU diff with Vim diff mode. When I run the diff from command line, it works. When I try to use the diff with Vim it doesn't work. What should I do now?"
There is a problem with using \s-1GNU\s0 diff with Vim. You can try using the
\&\s-1GNU\s0 diff.exe built by Ron Aaron from the following link:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& http://www.mossbayeng.com/~ron/vim/builds.html
.Ve
.SS "33.8. Is it possible to use Vim as an external editor for MS-Windows Outlook email client?"
.IX Subsection "33.8. Is it possible to use Vim as an external editor for MS-Windows Outlook email client?"
You can use the \*(L"cubiclevim\*(R" \s-1COM\s0 Add-In to use Vim as an external editor
for MS-Windows Outlook email client. Visit the following \s-1URL\s0 for more
information:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& http://sourceforge.net/projects/cubiclevim
.Ve
.PP
Note, that currently this works only with MS-Office 2000 and \s-1XP.\s0
.PP
Also the plugin OutlookVim might be worth a look:
.PP
http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=3087
.SS "33.9. I am using Vim to edit \s-1HTML\s0 files. How do I start internet explorer with the current file to preview the \s-1HTML\s0 file?"
.IX Subsection "33.9. I am using Vim to edit HTML files. How do I start internet explorer with the current file to preview the HTML file?"
You can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :!start c:\eprogra~1\eintern~1\eiexplore.exe file://%:p<CR>
.Ve
.SS "33.10. I would like to use Vim with Microsoft Visual Studio. How do I do this?"
.IX Subsection "33.10. I would like to use Vim with Microsoft Visual Studio. How do I do this?"
You have to download and use the \s-1OLE\s0 version of Vim (for example:
gvim61ole.zip). This file also contains instructions on how to use Vim with
Visual Studio.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help MSVisualStudio\fR
.SS "33.11. Where do I place the _vimrc and _gvimrc files?"
.IX Subsection "33.11. Where do I place the _vimrc and _gvimrc files?"
You can place the _vimrc and _gvimrc files under the directory pointed to
by the \s-1VIM\s0 environment variable. If you are sharing this system with other
users, then you can place the files in a directory and set the \s-1HOME\s0
environment variable to this directory.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \f(CB$HOME\fB\-use\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help _vimrc\fR
.SS "33.12. Every time I save a file, Vim warns about the file being changed outside of Vim. Why?"
.IX Subsection "33.12. Every time I save a file, Vim warns about the file being changed outside of Vim. Why?"
If you get the following warning message, every time you save a file:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& WARNING: The file has been changed since reading it!!!
\& Do you really want to write to it (y/n)?
.Ve
.PP
then this problem could be related to a bug in MS-Windows on the day
daylight saving time starts.  Vim remembers the timestamp of the file after
it was written.  Just before the next write the timestamp is obtained again
to check if the file was changed outside of Vim.  This works correctly,
except on the day daylight saving time starts.
.PP
This problem will go away the next day after the day the daylight saving
time starts.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help W11\fR
