.SS "36.1. How do I edit binary files with Vim?"
.IX Subsection "36.1. How do I edit binary files with Vim?"
You can set the following options to edit binary files in Vim:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& :set binary
\& :set display=uhex
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the \*(L"\-b\*(R" command-line option to edit a binary file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-b <binary_file_name>
.Ve
.PP
You can also use the xxd utility (part of the Vim distribution) to edit
binary files.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 23.4\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help edit-binary\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help hex-editing\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-b\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'binary'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'endofline'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'display'\fR
.SS "36.2. How do I disable the visual error flash and the error beep?"
.IX Subsection "36.2. How do I disable the visual error flash and the error beep?"
You can disable both the visual error flash and the error beep using the
following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set visualbell t_vb=
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'visualbell'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'errorbells'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help t_vb\fR
.SS "36.3. How do I display the ascii value of a character displayed in a buffer?"
.IX Subsection "36.3. How do I display the ascii value of a character displayed in a buffer?"
You can use the 'ga' command to display the ascii value of a displayed
character.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help ga\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help :ascii\fR
.SS "36.4. Can I use zero as a count for a Vim command?"
.IX Subsection "36.4. Can I use zero as a count for a Vim command?"
You cannot use zero as a count for a Vim command, as \*(L"0\*(R" is a command on
its own, moving to the first column of the line.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 0\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help count\fR
.SS "36.5. How do I disable the Vim welcome screen?"
.IX Subsection "36.5. How do I disable the Vim welcome screen?"
You can disable the Vim welcome screen, by adding the 'I' flag to the
\&'shortmess' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set shortmess+=I
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :intro\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'shortmess'\fR
.ie n .SS "36.6. How do I avoid the ""hit enter to continue"" prompt?"
.el .SS "36.6. How do I avoid the ``hit enter to continue'' prompt?"
.IX Subsection "36.6. How do I avoid the hit enter to continue prompt?"
Vim will prompt you with the \*(L"hit enter to continue\*(R" prompt, if there are
some messages on the screen for you to read and the screen is about to be
redrawn.  You can add the 'T' flag to the 'shortmess' option to truncate
all messages. This will help in avoiding the hit-enter prompt:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set shortmess+=T
.Ve
.PP
You can also increase the command height by setting the 'cmdheight' option:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& :set cmdheight=2
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help hit-enter\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help avoid-hit-enter\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'shortmess'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'cmdheight'\fR
.SS "36.7. How do I invoke Vim from command line to run a group of commands on a group of files?"
.IX Subsection "36.7. How do I invoke Vim from command line to run a group of commands on a group of files?"
There are several ways to invoke Vim from command line to run a group of
commands on a group of files. You can use a set of  \*(L"\-c\*(R" command line
options to specify a group of commands:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-c "<ex_command_1>" \-c "<ex_command_2>" *.txt
.Ve
.PP
Each of the ex-command specified with the \*(L"\-c\*(R" command line option is
executed one by one sequentially. You can also use a single \*(L"\-c\*(R" command
line option and the \*(L"|\*(R" character to separate the ex commands:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-c "<ex_command_1> | <ex_command_2>" *.txt
.Ve
.PP
In the above command, if an ex command fails, then all the remaining ex
commands will not be executed.
.PP
For example, to replace \*(L"\s-1ABC\*(R"\s0 with \*(L"\s-1DEF\*(R"\s0 in a file from the command-line,
you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-c "%s/ABC/DEF/ge | update" myfile.txt
.Ve
.PP
To replace \*(L"\s-1ABC\*(R"\s0 with \*(L"\s-1DEF\*(R"\s0 in multiple files from the command-line,
you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-c "argdo %s/ABC/DEF/ge | update" *.txt
.Ve
.PP
You can store the group of commands into a file and use the \*(L"\-s\*(R" command
line option to run the commands on a set of files. For example, if the
group of commands are stored in the file mycmds.txt, then you can use the
following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim \-s mycmds.txt *.pl
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help \-c\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help \-s\fR
.SS "36.8. How do I use a normal mode command from insert mode without leaving the insert mode?"
.IX Subsection "36.8. How do I use a normal mode command from insert mode without leaving the insert mode?"
You can use a normal command from insert mode, without leaving the insert
mode, by first pressing the CTRL-O key and then follow that with a single
normal mode command.
.PP
To execute more than one normal mode command, press the CTRL-L key,
followed by any number of normal mode commands and then press <Esc> to get
back to the insert mode. (This only works, when the 'insertmode' option
is set).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-O\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-L\fR
.SS "36.9. How do I start Vim in insert mode?"
.IX Subsection "36.9. How do I start Vim in insert mode?"
You can start Vim in insert mode using the \*(L":startinsert\*(R" ex command.
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim +startinsert myfile.txt
.Ve
.PP
The above command will open the file \*(L"myfile.txt\*(R" and start insert mode
with the cursor in front of the first character on the first line.  To open
the file and start appending after the last character on the last line,
you can use the following command:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $ vim + +startinsert! myfile.txt
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :startinsert\fR
.SS "36.10. How do I use Copy and Paste with Vim?"
.IX Subsection "36.10. How do I use Copy and Paste with Vim?"
You should first check the output of the \*(L":version\*(R" command and make
sure that +xterm\-clipboard is present.
.PP
When running Vim in an xterm, you can either let Vim control the mouse
or let xterm control the mouse. This is configured by the 'mouse' option.
.PP
If the 'mouse' option is not set (or set to the default value), then Vim will
not control the mouse. You cannot move the Vim text cursor using the
mouse. When you select some text using the mouse, xterm will copy
it to the X11 cut buffer. When you press both the mouse buttons,
xterm will paste the text from the cut buffer.
.PP
If the 'mouse' option is set to 'a' or some other value, then Vim controls
the mouse. The mode (normal or insert or visual, etc) in which Vim
controls the mouse is configured by the 'mouse' option. You can move
the Vim text cursor using the mouse. When you select some text,
the 'clipboard' option setting is used to determine whether to transfer
the selected text to the clipboard or not. The default setting is to
transfer the selected text to the clipboard. If you want to use the
xterm selection mechanism in this mode, then you can press the
<Shift> key. If you press <Shift> key when selecting text using the
mouse, then Vim doesn't control the mouse and xterm controls the
mouse.
.PP
In the \s-1GUI\s0 mode, Copy and Paste should just work, depending on the 'mouse'
setting. For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'clipboard'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help x11\-selection\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help clipboard\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'go\-a'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'mouse'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help xterm-copy-paste\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 09.3\fR
.SS "36.11. Why shouldn't I modify the files in the system runtime directory?"
.IX Subsection "36.11. Why shouldn't I modify the files in the system runtime directory?"
Just be careful about modifying files under \f(CW$VIMRUNTIME\fR, which usually
is /usr/share/vim/vimXX (Unix) or C:\eProgram Files\evim\evimXX
(Windows) and \s-1XX\s0 being the version for which it applies, e.g. 73 for Vim
=head2 7.3.
.PP
One should generally avoid modifying those files because they may be
replaced during an upgrade of your Vim installation and your changes
will be lost.  Also, if you upgrade to a new major or minor revision of
Vim (e.g., from 7.3 to 7.4), the new version of Vim will use a different
\&\f(CW$VIMRUNTIME\fR directory and while your changes won't be lost, they will be
ignored.
.PP
Consequently, take a look at
.PP
\&\fB:help filetypes\fR
.PP
for an explanation of several ways to modify Vim's response to
different filetypes and where to put those modifications so that
they will not be overwritten.
.SH "UNICODE"
.IX Header "UNICODE"
Author: Tony Mechelynck <antoine.mechelynck \s-1AT\s0 belgacom.net>
.SS "37.1. Is it possible to create Unicode files using Vim?"
.IX Subsection "37.1. Is it possible to create Unicode files using Vim?"
Yes. It may be more or less complicated depending on the keyboard and fonts
available to you, but it is always possible to encode any possible Unicode
codepoint (and some illegal ones) into a file. To create a Unicode file
using Vim, you should have compiled Vim with the \*(L"+multi_byte\*(R" compile-time
option.  You can get more information about Unicode from the following
sites:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& http://www.unicode.org
\& http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~mgk25/unicode.html
.Ve
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help multibyte\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help usr_45.txt\fR
.SS "37.2. Which Vim settings are particularly important for editing Unicode files?"
.IX Subsection "37.2. Which Vim settings are particularly important for editing Unicode files?"
The most important are the various \*(L"encoding\*(R" options, i.e., 'encoding',
\&'fileencoding', 'fileencodings' and 'termencoding'. The boolean option
\&'bomb' is also significant.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'encoding'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileencoding'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileencodings'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'termencoding'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'bomb'\fR
.SS "37.3. What is the 'encoding' option?"
.IX Subsection "37.3. What is the 'encoding' option?"
Basically, the 'encoding' option defines how Vim will represent your data
internally.  However, all Unicode encodings are represented internally as
utf\-8 and converted (if necessary) when reading and writing.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'encoding'\fR
.SS "37.4. How does Vim name the various Unicode encodings?"
.IX Subsection "37.4. How does Vim name the various Unicode encodings?"
Utf\-8 is called utf\-8 or utf8; utf\-16 is called ucs\-2 or ucs2; utf\-32 is
called ucs\-4 or ucs4. Also, you may specify endianness (except for utf\-8
which does not vary for endianness) by appending le for little-endian or be
for big-endian. If you create a file with an encoding of ucs\-2 or ucs\-4
without specifying endianness, Vim will use what is typical of your
machine.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help encoding-names\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help encoding-values\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help encoding-table\fR
.SS "37.5. How does Vim specify the presence or absence of a byte-order mark?"
.IX Subsection "37.5. How does Vim specify the presence or absence of a byte-order mark?"
When reading a file, if the 'fileencodings' option includes \*(L"ucs-bom\*(R", Vim
will check for a byte-order mark. When writing a file, if the 'bomb' option
is set, Vim will write a byte-order mark on files whose encoding warrants
it.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileencodings'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'bomb'\fR
.SS "37.6. What is the 'fileencoding' option?"
.IX Subsection "37.6. What is the 'fileencoding' option?"
The 'fileencoding' option defines the particular encoding which Vim will
use to write a file. If empty, then the value of the 'encoding' option is
the default.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileencoding'\fR
.SS "37.7. What is the 'fileencodings' option?"
.IX Subsection "37.7. What is the 'fileencodings' option?"
The 'fileencodings' option defines the heuristics used by Vim when opening
an existing file. It is a comma separated list of encodings. A special
name, \*(L"ucs-bom\*(R" is used to indicate that Vim should check for the presence
of a byte-order mark; however, it will not be recognised if it comes after
\&\*(L"utf\-8\*(R".  Normally, \*(L"ucs-bom\*(R" (if present) should be first in the list.
.PP
When Vim opens a file, it checks it against the encodings listed in
\&'fileencodings'. The first one that matches is used. If there is no match,
then Vim sets 'fileencoding' to the null string, i.e., the value of
\&'encoding' will be used.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'fileencodings'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'encoding'\fR
.SS "37.8. What is the 'termencoding' option?"
.IX Subsection "37.8. What is the 'termencoding' option?"
The 'termencoding' option defines how your keyboard encodes the data you
type.  If empty, Vim assumes that it has the same value as 'encoding'.
Usually it should be set to something that matches your locale.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'termencoding'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help locale\fR
.SS "37.9. What is the 'bomb' option?"
.IX Subsection "37.9. What is the 'bomb' option?"
When reading a file with \*(L"ucs-bom\*(R" present in the 'fileencodings' option,
Vim will set the 'bomb' option on or off depending on the presence or
absence of a byte-order mark at the start of the file. When writing, Vim
will write a byte-order mark if the 'bomb' option is set. You may set or
unset it manually do make Vim write, or not write, the b.o.m.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help 'bomb'\fR
.SS "37.10. Where can I find an example of a typical use of all these options?"
.IX Subsection "37.10. Where can I find an example of a typical use of all these options?"
There is a \*(L"tip\*(R", with explains them in different words with an example, at
.PP
http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/VimTip246
.SS "37.11. How can I insert Unicode characters into a file using Vim?"
.IX Subsection "37.11. How can I insert Unicode characters into a file using Vim?"
Several methods are available:
.PP
\&\- Characters present on your keyboard can be typed in the usual way, even
  those which require a \*(L"dead-key\*(R" prefix, like (for instance) the
  circumflex on French keyboards.
\&\- Characters for which a digraph is defined can be typed as two characters
  prefixed by <Ctrl\-K>.
\&\- If you have set the 'digraph' option, you can enter the characters for
  which a digraph is defined as <char1><\s-1BS\s0><char2>.
\&\- Any character can be entered by using a <Ctrl\-V> prefix (or <Ctrl\-Q> if
  <Ctrl\-V> is remapped to paste from the clipboard).
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help digraphs\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'digraph'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help i_CTRL\-V_digit\fR
.SS "37.12. How can I know which digraphs are defined and for which characters?"
.IX Subsection "37.12. How can I know which digraphs are defined and for which characters?"
First set the 'encoding' option properly (for instance, to utf\-8), then use
the :digraphs command to list the currently defined digraphs.
.PP
Alternatively, the help file contains the complete set of all digraphs.
So you can easily search that list there.
.PP
For more information, read
.PP
\&\fB:help :digraphs\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help 'encoding'\fR
.PP
\&\fB:help digraph-table\fR
